WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:05.600
Is the romantic archetype of the great artist finished? And if so, what is replacing it?

00:06.800 --> 00:14.480
No, I don't think it is finished. I think there are still absolutely great artists who produce

00:14.480 --> 00:21.040
work that's on a level with which only a small few others produce anything comparable.

00:21.840 --> 00:28.800
And I think you can find hierarchies of artistic production in most

00:30.000 --> 00:36.800
cultures in the world and in most periods in history. Whether the particular archetype

00:36.800 --> 00:43.920
that was promoted by the romantics and the idea of the somewhat aloof artist and the

00:43.920 --> 00:49.520
artist as a seer of special truths not really available to anyone else. Whether that has the

00:49.520 --> 00:54.880
same currency today as it might have had in the early 90s century, I'm less sure. But I still think

00:54.880 --> 01:04.160
there are absolutely great artists and I still think it's important that art forms a type of

01:04.160 --> 01:10.640
activity which interacts with a wider society but doesn't just simply mirror it or isn't simply

01:10.640 --> 01:17.360
determined with it by it. So I do believe in art existing in a dialectical relationship with the

01:17.360 --> 01:24.000
rest of society and culture. And I do distinguish the words art and culture and that's even allowing

01:24.000 --> 01:29.520
for multiple different meanings of the term culture itself. Right. Well, there are those who would

01:29.520 --> 01:33.840
say that the very idea of the great artist is something that should be called into question

01:33.840 --> 01:40.880
in the sense that it seems to indicate what would you say, well, a hierarchy to begin with,

01:40.880 --> 01:46.800
a hierarchy of competence or of importance that some would call into question. They would instead

01:46.800 --> 01:52.560
espouse perhaps a more flat horizon, a more flat landscape in which everybody potentially can

01:52.560 --> 01:59.120
contribute as opposed to the, I'm caricaturing this perhaps, but the great man archetype of

01:59.120 --> 02:03.360
people like Stravinsky, T.S. Eliot, Kandinsky, Schoenberg and so on.

02:04.400 --> 02:11.840
Well, I'd ask if they would extend that anti-hierarchical view into popular culture, say. I mean,

02:12.800 --> 02:19.120
would they say that the reason why Taylor Swift or Beyoncé are such global superstars compared

02:19.120 --> 02:23.120
to many others that only a small community ever heard of, is that entirely arbitrary?

02:24.480 --> 02:29.920
Is that not something to do with how they sing, how they dance, how they perform, the things that

02:29.920 --> 02:35.120
they do sing or whatever? I mean, this is putting whatever views I might have about either of those

02:35.360 --> 02:42.800
artists to one side, but I don't really believe anyone truly thinks that there are no distinctions

02:42.800 --> 02:50.560
and no hierarchies between different types of artists in whatever form. And, you know, if it's

02:50.560 --> 02:54.960
just down to a simpler thing as a conversation between two people who've been watching something

02:54.960 --> 02:59.760
on television the previous evening, they'll often talk about what they thought of it,

02:59.840 --> 03:06.400
how good it was. One might think it's better than the other does. You're already setting up a hierarchy

03:06.400 --> 03:14.240
in that very process. Value judgment, I think, is a very common and perhaps even intrinsic human

03:14.240 --> 03:20.720
activity when confronted with art, confronted with culture. And it's only perhaps a small few

03:20.720 --> 03:26.320
academics, including semester musicologists and anthropologists, who seem to think you can

03:27.200 --> 03:33.680
totally bracket out value judgment or is it somehow, it's some great sin. I don't think so.

03:33.680 --> 03:38.560
I think it goes on all the time. And the moment you have value judgments about any culture,

03:38.560 --> 03:42.000
then you create hierarchies between those who produce it.

03:42.000 --> 03:47.040
Okay. I want to stay on this question of artistic greatness, of the great artist for a moment,

03:47.040 --> 03:52.720
because this is very much on my mind at present. First of all, how would you define a great artist

03:52.720 --> 03:57.520
in the present day context? What would that sort of a figure do and what would their role be within

03:57.520 --> 04:04.880
society? Right. Well, those are two quite different questions, I think. I mean, very simply,

04:05.840 --> 04:10.000
I'd say a great artist is one who produces a lot of great art, but I realize that doesn't

04:10.000 --> 04:18.800
really answer the question then what constitutes great art. And I'm not sure if I can really

04:19.040 --> 04:25.440
answer that question in any sort of comprehensive way. I can believe that such a thing like great

04:25.440 --> 04:32.720
art does exist. But why exactly it's great and it's so much greater than a lot of other things

04:32.720 --> 04:37.920
is often quite a complex question and needs to be addressed in each individual case.

04:38.640 --> 04:42.240
If you could say this is what makes great art, that almost suggests that there's a

04:42.240 --> 04:46.720
formula for producing it, which I don't believe there is.

04:46.720 --> 04:52.240
Well, I think to start with, just to unravel this a little bit, the greatness of the art

04:52.240 --> 04:56.880
does not reside only in the art itself. So it has something to do with the way the

04:56.880 --> 05:01.600
art or indeed the artist interfaces with their society. And the greatness has something to do

05:01.600 --> 05:08.640
with magnitude, to use a word that is perhaps not ideal, but the impact that the artist may be

05:08.640 --> 05:16.640
having or may not be having. If the work is great but exists in a drawer and is not doing

05:16.640 --> 05:24.160
anything real in the world besides merely existing, then can we ascribe greatness to that?

05:25.760 --> 05:31.840
Well, last year I went to see the Vermeer exhibition that was on in Amsterdam, which is

05:31.840 --> 05:37.360
absolutely incredible, probably the greatest art exhibition I've ever seen. Now I know that

05:37.360 --> 05:41.840
Vermeer's paintings languished relatively unknown for quite an extended period until

05:41.840 --> 05:44.560
they were rediscovered. I think it was some point in the 19th century.

05:48.480 --> 05:54.640
Now they didn't have the impact that they have now in the earlier times, and they didn't have

05:54.640 --> 06:00.560
a critical scholarly apparatus that developed around them, and which I do believe conditions

06:00.560 --> 06:05.120
to some extent the reception of art, and I don't mean that in a negative way.

06:06.080 --> 06:13.520
But I don't see any necessary reason why if they hadn't had that in earlier times,

06:13.520 --> 06:17.360
they wouldn't have been thought just as great then. So what I'm trying to say from that is,

06:17.360 --> 06:24.640
I don't think the reasons we think Vermeer is great now are limited to our current temporal

06:24.640 --> 06:30.400
moment. I think it's something much more intrinsic in the art, which gives the potential for a

06:30.400 --> 06:36.640
particular level of impact. But I don't think that is something grafted on artificially. I think

06:36.640 --> 06:42.800
that has to somehow come out of the intrinsic qualities of the art itself, which to me is sort

06:42.800 --> 06:50.160
of self-evidently monumental in Vermeer's case. So I'm just trying to remember the rest of your

06:50.160 --> 06:57.200
question. Well, would there be... Is it more difficult to make a claim for greatness if the

06:57.200 --> 07:04.640
artist is addressing perhaps an extraordinarily restricted audience, or perhaps even no one at

07:04.640 --> 07:09.760
all, as opposed to... The Vermeer case is interesting because you could certainly put forth the argument

07:09.760 --> 07:16.640
that Vermeer is addressing very simple universal concepts in his work that speak to a large number

07:16.640 --> 07:24.000
of people. If we get into modernism and wherever it is we are now, you get into an archetype of

07:24.000 --> 07:34.080
an artist that is extraordinarily, in many instances, detached from the reality of the

07:34.080 --> 07:41.520
society in which they're living. And perhaps even dealing with artistic aesthetic concepts that are

07:41.520 --> 07:47.120
so esoteric by their very nature that such universality, though it may be buried in there

07:47.120 --> 07:50.800
somewhere, is going to be extraordinarily difficult for most people to locate.

07:50.800 --> 07:56.640
I'll take two of the examples that you suggested before, Stravinsky and T.S. Eliot.

07:58.640 --> 08:06.880
The means that they were using for conveying their art might have been, to some extent,

08:06.880 --> 08:12.000
esoteric at the time, perhaps more so in Eliot's case than at least the early Stravinsky,

08:13.920 --> 08:17.920
but I think they were dealing with concerns that were extremely

08:18.880 --> 08:25.920
urgent at the time. In the early Stravinsky dealing with issues of primitivism, of folklorism,

08:25.920 --> 08:32.320
with stylized barbarism and so on, which, for the works he was writing at the beginning of the

08:32.320 --> 08:38.000
1910s, they now look incredibly prescient, I think, in knowledge of what happened in the

08:38.000 --> 08:42.720
succeeding decades. In the case of Eliot, I mean, he was engaging with popular culture,

08:42.720 --> 08:53.600
with sort of popular song and ballads and things like that, and looking at the modern city and the

08:53.600 --> 09:02.080
whole alienation that came with that, and looking at the state of religion in his own time. These

09:02.080 --> 09:08.400
were not very simply private concerns to Eliot himself. The way he assembled these into his

09:08.400 --> 09:15.120
montage, like works of quite heavily, I would say, inspired by sort of Baudelaire's view of the city

09:15.120 --> 09:24.560
as well, might have been part of a technical approach that was at that stage relatively

09:24.560 --> 09:32.000
unfamiliar to readers, but those things have become absorbed into a much wider cultural

09:32.000 --> 09:40.560
vernaculars. And so I suppose in both cases, I am questioning whether this work really was so cut

09:40.560 --> 09:45.520
off from society, whether it was so esoteric, because I think it was dealing with sort of

09:45.520 --> 09:50.480
very socially, in both cases, they were dealing with very socially and politically urgent things,

09:50.480 --> 09:57.920
and I think they remain so. Now in their cases, whether those would still remain so in 200 years

09:57.920 --> 10:05.280
from now, well, I can only guess. I believe so. I mean, again, I'm speculating there, but

10:05.280 --> 10:12.960
I believe so in the same way that, you know, I can read Dante nowadays, and that is incredibly vivid

10:12.960 --> 10:22.960
to me. Some of the more esoteric pieces of medieval theology take at least some sort of

10:23.040 --> 10:28.320
extra annotations to understand, I find, certainly stuff in parody so. But nonetheless,

10:29.120 --> 10:38.640
as a narrative, as a form of social commentary, when this incredible thing of deciding which

10:38.640 --> 10:45.200
circles of hell you will consign people, you know, and public figures to, I think it's absolutely

10:45.200 --> 10:53.200
gripping, even though it dates from the best part of a millennium ago. And I don't necessarily see

10:53.200 --> 11:00.240
any reason why Stravinsky and Eliot won't be the same. I do think some very, very topical art

11:00.240 --> 11:08.400
that deals with very, very much issues of their time, which do not necessarily project out much

11:08.400 --> 11:16.480
further, tends to date a lot more. And this is a reason that I'm quite skeptical about a lot of

11:16.480 --> 11:24.240
explicitly political art. No, not all. It's stuff that's absolutely rooted in response to concrete

11:24.240 --> 11:31.760
events. Well, there's various reasons that I'm skeptical about it. One is the obvious one that

11:31.760 --> 11:38.960
when those events cease to be current, the art loses a lot of its immediacy. But there's also

11:38.960 --> 11:43.680
the issue of whether there's something exploitative about this, whether it's sort of rendering a

11:43.680 --> 11:48.000
trustee's into art, whether it's taking some of the edge off them by rendering them aesthetic,

11:48.000 --> 11:52.320
which is sort of how Adorno's critique of that worked.

11:52.320 --> 11:56.480
Well, unless there's something in the style and substance of the work that is so transcendently

11:56.480 --> 12:02.080
interesting that the pretext for its creation simply falls by the wayside. So for instance,

12:02.080 --> 12:08.560
if you take, this is a random example, I suppose, but if you take the novels or the journalistic

12:08.560 --> 12:13.680
work of Hunter S. Thompson, so the things that he was describing at the time are no longer of

12:13.680 --> 12:22.640
particular public interest, their political events or events of the day that are now decades

12:22.720 --> 12:28.400
beyond us. But nevertheless, there's something in the style, in the substance of those works

12:28.400 --> 12:31.920
that is phenomenally interesting and that transcends the original subject matter.

12:32.480 --> 12:38.240
So in the best case, in the best case, I think that the work can survive on that basis.

12:39.040 --> 12:46.880
I absolutely agree. And that's a sort of testament to quite what a good writer Hunter S. Thompson

12:46.880 --> 12:53.920
was. It's why it's probably a mistake to see his work primarily in terms of specific events

12:54.560 --> 12:59.600
that he's looking at, but rather in terms of the much wider concerns that he's drawing out of them.

12:59.600 --> 13:04.160
And yes, I could say that about any number of other things. I could say that about Guernica, for example.

13:08.560 --> 13:11.680
So where does that leave the statement that I was just making before?

13:11.840 --> 13:17.600
I think it's about sort of distinguishing,

13:20.400 --> 13:25.040
I'm going to use some very old fashioned vocabulary here, distinguishing between

13:25.680 --> 13:30.880
human concerns and localised political concerns.

13:31.760 --> 13:40.480
Now, what would I'm trying to think of some other examples? I mean this...

13:41.680 --> 13:47.840
Ode to Napoleon, for example, or the Eroica Symphony. I mean, you're entering into the realm

13:47.840 --> 13:54.480
of archetypes and symbols and that, so there may be a contemporary pretext for producing the work.

13:55.280 --> 13:58.480
It may refer on some level to a contemporary figure.

13:59.200 --> 14:02.960
Well, let me give you another example of something of the opposite tendency,

14:02.960 --> 14:07.280
but it's actually someone whose work I rather like. I don't know if you know his British playwright,

14:07.280 --> 14:08.400
James Graham. No.

14:08.960 --> 14:13.040
All right. Well, there's probably a reason why you don't know him and probably not many people

14:13.040 --> 14:18.560
outside of Britain know him. He's very obsessed with British politics, as am I,

14:19.680 --> 14:24.800
and he's written a whole load of plays which are dramatising particular events in British politics.

14:25.760 --> 14:32.560
He wrote a play called The House, which is set in the House of Commons during the 70s,

14:32.560 --> 14:37.920
and it's set in the whips office, the people who are whip up support for things, and it follows

14:37.920 --> 14:44.080
all the machinations that go on and how exactly they manipulate people to get their vote. At a

14:44.080 --> 14:50.720
particular time in British history where the Labour Party who were in power lost their majority

14:50.720 --> 14:56.240
in the House of Commons through losing various by-elections, and even before they lost it,

14:56.240 --> 15:03.760
it was down to one or two votes could mean whether they would lose or win some parliamentary votes.

15:05.680 --> 15:10.560
Now, he traces this, and if you're interested in that, which I am, it's absolutely fascinating,

15:10.560 --> 15:16.720
and he wrote a screenplay about how the Brexit campaign was managed by Dominic Cummings,

15:16.720 --> 15:25.120
who was played by Benedict Cumberbatch in that. I say I enjoy his things, I'll always go and watch

15:25.920 --> 15:33.120
the new ones, but I can see if you don't have that very specialised interest, I'm not sure how much

15:33.120 --> 15:37.520
else would come out. I suppose something about the way the business of politics works in general,

15:38.480 --> 15:43.600
for which parallels could be found in other contexts as well, but I think it goes quite

15:44.400 --> 15:49.920
on those things, and so I'd say I like seeing them, but they're not particularly

15:49.920 --> 15:58.080
places I'd want to see many times, or that I imagine will have any sort of long lasting sort

15:58.080 --> 16:06.000
of impact. So I suppose that's what I'm thinking of. The other objections that I'm saying about

16:06.000 --> 16:14.240
political art, I think are possibly more vivid in their own way. So I have problems, even with

16:14.240 --> 16:20.720
the work like Luigi Nono's D'Gorda Cosi di Hanno Fatou in Auschwitz, which was written as originally

16:20.720 --> 16:28.560
as incidental music for Peter Weiss's play Die Ermittlung, the investigation, which was essentially

16:28.560 --> 16:34.640
a reconstruction of parts of the Frankfurt Auschwitz trials. And in his programme note for the work,

16:34.720 --> 16:42.480
Nono himself says that what the transcripts of the trials can't represent is

16:43.840 --> 16:50.000
the voice of the Six Million Dead, and that's what he wants to do in his music. Now I think,

16:50.000 --> 16:55.680
first of all, that's incredibly presumptuous, and I don't think any artist should claim to be

16:56.240 --> 17:05.120
doing that. But beyond that, it's a strangely very beautiful piece. It's a very haunting piece.

17:06.720 --> 17:12.720
It's a piece, dare I say, to enjoy. And when you can see where I'm leading from that,

17:13.840 --> 17:20.880
it's turning genocide into an aesthetic spectacle. So if Adorno said, at one point,

17:20.880 --> 17:25.120
I know he retracted this later, he said there could be no lyric poetry after Auschwitz.

17:25.200 --> 17:31.360
Well, this is making lyric poetry out of Auschwitz, which is moving on to a whole different level.

17:32.320 --> 17:35.600
And I just don't think it's an appropriate response.

17:35.600 --> 17:40.160
It's funny, I had a similar reaction to a much more recent piece, which is

17:40.160 --> 17:45.680
The Opera Innocence by Caio Sarriaho, which is an opera dealing with school shootings.

17:46.720 --> 17:48.000
Oh yes, I haven't seen it.

17:48.000 --> 17:52.640
Right. Well, it documents the story of a school shooting in quite

17:53.600 --> 17:59.440
quite horrendous detail and presents this as an aesthetic object, I suppose. And

18:00.880 --> 18:06.640
that made me intensely uncomfortable. And you could argue, well, that's perhaps the

18:06.640 --> 18:12.400
point is to put that in your face and present the reality of it in a context where one might

18:12.400 --> 18:19.520
not be expecting such a thing. But it seemed to me at the time, and this is acknowledging

18:19.600 --> 18:23.360
the greatness of the work. I think it is her best opera. I think it's a very fine work.

18:23.360 --> 18:30.160
The musical substance of it is outstanding. But nevertheless, it raised a question in my mind,

18:30.160 --> 18:34.640
is this actually appropriate? Is this something that one can address in an opera?

18:36.000 --> 18:41.040
Well, I'm interested to know more about the types of musical means she used and

18:41.840 --> 18:46.720
what you think made it particularly a set as size there. But I suppose the question I would

18:46.720 --> 18:53.040
always ask there is, why is this an opera? Why is it not a film? Why is it not a play?

18:53.040 --> 19:00.800
Why is it not a documentary even? I remember someone talking about a projected piece

19:02.160 --> 19:09.280
that would deal with the phenomenon of punch and duty shows here and what that meant in terms of

19:09.280 --> 19:15.760
domestic violence at the time. You know, very relevant concern, absolutely. But I was, I never

19:15.760 --> 19:21.680
really got around to asking them, why is this piece of music there? And why are you using a

19:21.680 --> 19:30.080
particular artistic medium? And it's something I wonder about a lot of work I see nowadays,

19:30.080 --> 19:38.560
where I think the nominal subject matter seems to have an importance way over and above what

19:38.560 --> 19:45.040
the musical content is. And somehow it's seen by some as to render questions of the musical value

19:45.040 --> 19:51.200
almost irrelevant. But in the end, if it is a work of music, I want to know why

19:51.200 --> 20:03.360
music's being used for this. I mean, supposing I want to get off a sort of Nazi example,

20:03.360 --> 20:10.800
because those are so full of problems. But I could imagine someone setting a gulag chorus or

20:10.800 --> 20:17.200
something in opera, and I could imagine this being absolutely dreadful, if it was done a certain way.

20:17.200 --> 20:24.800
It could make light of the gulag experience so much. And you know, I can think of other things,

20:24.800 --> 20:32.400
even in opera, I like very much Billy Bird of Britain, but I know how brutalising the conditions

20:32.400 --> 20:37.040
were in the Royal Navy at that time. Now, I mean, some of that comes across certainly

20:37.040 --> 20:43.120
through the flogging scene and things like that. But when you see them singing their sea shanties

20:44.080 --> 20:51.520
at night, there's a sort of sense that they've found some reasonably happy reconciliation

20:51.520 --> 20:58.880
to their lot. That might have been a necessity, for sure. But somehow it just seems all a bit too

20:58.880 --> 21:04.800
warm at that point. I mean, I'm probably being a bit harsh on that, because that opera certainly

21:04.800 --> 21:12.000
does deal in some senses with other aspects. But yes, I'm back again to the question of why

21:13.360 --> 21:18.480
use music, particularly why I have something sung rather than spoken, or why even fictionalise

21:18.480 --> 21:25.120
something in some cases. Now, I can certainly see arguments for doing so in even including

21:25.120 --> 21:30.240
things which are dealing with greater atrocities. Sometimes a fiction can reveal a reality that

21:30.240 --> 21:38.480
a documentary approach might not. But I think these questions can easily be treated rather too

21:38.480 --> 21:46.320
lightly. We've come off with a bit of a tangent, and I feel like I need to return to some thread,

21:46.320 --> 21:51.600
but I've forgotten exactly where we were. You were talking about Sarajah's opera,

21:52.560 --> 21:59.600
which I really want to see, and I haven't seen now. And I was thinking of other examples,

22:00.000 --> 22:05.920
well, there's a piece I wrote for the conversation a few years ago, where I looked a bit critically

22:05.920 --> 22:11.920
at the Nanna work, and also at Penderecki's Threnadie, which, as we know, was given its title

22:11.920 --> 22:18.320
about Hiroshima after it was composed. The very fact of that makes me a bit skeptical,

22:18.880 --> 22:26.800
where this is sort of appropriating a traumatic event to artificially sort of

22:27.360 --> 22:31.280
paced on some relevance to our work. Opportunistically also, yes, yeah.

22:31.280 --> 22:36.000
But as comparing with actually a more musically conservative work in some senses,

22:36.000 --> 22:42.640
but I do think it's remarkable being Shostakovich's 13th Symphony after poems by Yev Deschenko

22:42.640 --> 22:46.880
to do in part with the Babiyar massacre, there is actually a range of poems, they deal with

22:46.880 --> 22:56.720
several subjects. But that simply doesn't become is a type of atrocity pornography

22:57.600 --> 23:02.560
and I think it's remarkable for that, Shostakovich resists that temptation

23:04.080 --> 23:10.560
to write some sort of, some sort of Lamentosa work, which will never be sufficient for the scale

23:10.560 --> 23:16.640
of what's being represented. So no, I think it's a piece that actually invites a form of active

23:16.640 --> 23:22.720
rational engagement with what it's doing, rather than using it as for some sort of emotional

23:22.720 --> 23:31.120
catharsis. And maybe that's the thing, I think using, using traumatic events for that purpose,

23:31.120 --> 23:37.840
I think is in questionable taste at the very limit. And I've, you know, I've written a bit

23:38.560 --> 23:46.880
recently about endless pieces we get about climate change. It's very fashionable to write

23:46.880 --> 23:52.320
a piece about climate change. Now, if I'm going to look critically at this, don't think for a moment

23:52.320 --> 23:58.400
this means I'm trying to sort of, in a sense, minimize the importance of climate change as an

23:58.400 --> 24:04.560
issue, I think it's absolutely urgent and the consequences are incredibly serious in so many

24:04.560 --> 24:12.640
respects. But I just wonder what people are doing by writing a piece of music about it,

24:12.640 --> 24:18.720
which will probably get heard by a small community of listeners in the new music world,

24:18.720 --> 24:23.120
few of who will need convincing that climate change is a bad thing,

24:24.960 --> 24:29.200
whether it's really, whether these things are really adding to our understanding

24:29.200 --> 24:31.280
any more so than could be done by other means.

24:32.640 --> 24:35.920
Well, I suspect it's a form of in-group affirmation,

24:36.880 --> 24:39.440
ultimately. And there's a lot of that in the new music community.

24:40.240 --> 24:45.840
Sure. And that's not new. I mean, some of the political references even in Mozart operas may

24:45.840 --> 24:53.200
have actually taken the same form that when he was writing Don Giovanni's singing Viva la Libertà,

24:54.160 --> 25:00.560
he wasn't particularly saying something to his audiences as to some of his patrons to show that

25:00.560 --> 25:07.120
he was in support of a particular political direction there. So in a sense, that was a type

25:07.120 --> 25:14.240
of virtue signalling to an in-crowd as well. But I think, I mean, I don't, it would be too harsh

25:14.240 --> 25:22.720
just to condemn such things out of hand. I suppose I'm bothered when I think these become the primary

25:22.720 --> 25:29.280
focus of attention. And the rest of the music doesn't seem to count for very much. And I see this

25:30.400 --> 25:38.880
certainly in academic contexts with music, where ultimately, there are many composers

25:38.880 --> 25:45.520
employed by universities who are often writing in and in some sort of what I might say post-Avancard

25:45.520 --> 25:51.600
idiom for now, which draws upon some of the techniques and styles and genres that were

25:51.600 --> 25:57.760
associated with the avant-garde at its peak, rather necessarily developing wholly new ones.

25:59.360 --> 26:08.160
But in a language which will ultimately be esoteric to many academic managers,

26:08.160 --> 26:14.240
to many research funding bodies, to many of the other people that they have to please in order

26:14.240 --> 26:22.160
to secure a solid future within academia. And so if they can link their piece to other things,

26:22.160 --> 26:28.480
which are not in themselves, anything necessary to do with music, this is a good career strategy.

26:30.160 --> 26:32.400
If that sounds a bit of cynical views, because it is.

26:33.360 --> 26:38.480
Those two things are not necessarily mutually exclusive. You can have an optimized career

26:38.480 --> 26:45.760
strategy and also be a great artist. And in fact, I think the great artist who is hopelessly unable

26:47.440 --> 26:53.680
to communicate with anybody who is socially inept and who can't make a strong case for their work

26:53.680 --> 26:56.240
is going to be at a significant disadvantage, I would imagine.

26:56.880 --> 27:04.080
Yeah, no, I do agree with that. But I think it's possible to make a case for work in

27:05.360 --> 27:13.920
other terms. But I recognize that's hard for those working in particular, as I say, post-Avancard

27:14.640 --> 27:23.040
idioms. And that might actually say something reluctant, though I am, to go down this road about

27:24.000 --> 27:29.920
whether it's ever possible that those idioms in themselves can have any wider communicative

27:29.920 --> 27:35.120
potential. Well, communicative is probably not the best word. The whole series of communications

27:35.120 --> 27:42.320
have their own sorts of qualities, which are not necessarily the best, the most applicable

27:42.320 --> 27:51.040
to music. Maybe I like using the word, though it's become a bit of a cliche, resonance, or whether

27:51.040 --> 27:57.040
the music resonates and it's got a literal musical dimension to it. As I say, it's just

27:57.040 --> 28:01.920
become a little bit overused to become hackneyed. But I think it's possible that music can resonate

28:01.920 --> 28:08.480
rather than, in some sense, conveying a meaning. Or it can be meaningful without having a meaning.

28:08.480 --> 28:16.400
It doesn't have an object in the same way as, say, figurative art does, or a lot of uses of language

28:16.720 --> 28:24.640
can. Well, it's certainly possible for esoteric aesthetic directions to communicate to a very

28:24.640 --> 28:29.920
large number of people. That's happened on many occasions. The classic example is possibly the

28:29.920 --> 28:35.680
Right of Spring, which is enormously popular work and has an immediate power of seduction

28:35.680 --> 28:43.520
and expression that is self-evident. As for where that may stand in the present day, I'm

28:44.080 --> 28:51.280
considerably less convinced about composers able to take what might be by contemporary standards

28:53.120 --> 28:59.840
might be, let's say, esoteric or aesthetics that notably diverge from

29:00.880 --> 29:05.120
the bulk of musical practices in the composition world and manage to find a large

29:05.120 --> 29:08.720
audience doing that. I don't know. I think that that would be extraordinarily difficult.

29:08.720 --> 29:14.000
I haven't seen too many examples of that, certainly. And if I were to survey the composition

29:14.000 --> 29:18.560
landscape of the past 30 or 40 years, what are the individual works that have had anything like

29:19.840 --> 29:26.080
even an iota of significance in comparison with the work Like the Right of Spring?

29:26.080 --> 29:30.880
Now, you could argue that's something that reveals itself over time, that we need decades,

29:30.880 --> 29:37.040
perhaps half a century or more before the work reveals itself in its full dimensions.

29:37.520 --> 29:44.960
But I don't think that's necessarily the case. There are certainly works that find a broad audience

29:44.960 --> 29:51.840
and create a significant impact very shortly after their premiere. It just doesn't seem to be

29:51.840 --> 29:58.960
happening. And this is something that emerged as a kind of light motif in the discussions I had with

30:00.160 --> 30:05.360
intellectuals, public figures, people from the business world who attended the art conference

30:05.360 --> 30:09.760
in London back in October. Now, I had the opportunity to exchange with quite a number

30:09.760 --> 30:14.640
of people at that event, including prominent intellectuals from all sides of the political

30:14.640 --> 30:22.640
spectrum. And one recurring motif was the question, what are the artists doing? Where are they? Where

30:22.640 --> 30:27.200
have they gone? Where are the great figures of today? We mentioned T.S. Eliot and Stravinsky as

30:27.200 --> 30:34.080
two sort of emblematic examples, but is there anybody today who can claim to have anything

30:34.080 --> 30:43.440
like that measure of public notoriety, significance, critical attention? I'm quite doubtful about that.

30:44.320 --> 30:50.000
At least maybe not in the high cultural field, in popular cultural fields and possibly.

30:50.960 --> 30:57.600
I'm not sure right now, but at least in the last 50 years, I can think of figures there.

30:58.960 --> 31:01.840
You know, I can think of various popular musicians, I can think of jazz musicians,

31:01.840 --> 31:07.360
late jazz musicians, because I sort of think jazz morphed into other things around about

31:07.360 --> 31:18.400
the time of the 1970s onwards. Well, that's sort of what I call the one last push theory,

31:19.120 --> 31:24.640
that if we wait a bit of time and we push things like new music just a bit more,

31:24.640 --> 31:29.040
eventually, audiences will come around. Right. No, this is... I mean, I don't believe that.

31:29.040 --> 31:34.080
I don't believe that for a second. The idea, and this has been floated since at least the 1950s,

31:34.080 --> 31:38.400
if not longer, is that, well, it's because audiences aren't familiar enough with it,

31:38.400 --> 31:42.640
so if you can educate them, if you can explain to them what's going on in the work,

31:42.640 --> 31:45.600
then they'll come around to it. The problem is that they don't have the context,

31:45.600 --> 31:49.200
they don't understand what artists are doing, so you need to be an advocate,

31:49.200 --> 31:52.560
you need to explain it to them, and so on. In my experience, that simply doesn't work.

31:52.880 --> 32:00.320
There are branches of new music that simply do not have the capacity, I believe, to communicate

32:00.320 --> 32:04.480
broadly to a large number of people, and it's to do with the work. It's not to do with

32:05.600 --> 32:11.200
deficiencies in the sensibility or the education or the experience of the people who are listening.

32:12.080 --> 32:18.560
Now, that's an attitude that you see quite commonly in modernist composers such as

32:18.560 --> 32:24.000
Eliot Carter, who is constantly saying things along the lines that, well, the music is difficult,

32:24.000 --> 32:28.880
but people will just have to become more clever, and, well, where does that lead you?

32:29.920 --> 32:37.280
Well, can I take a sort of middle ground position on this? I go home after I've been working hard

32:38.000 --> 32:50.080
someday, and I don't always want to read some Goethe. I don't always want to be

32:50.880 --> 33:00.320
watching some classic Japanese cinema. I don't always want to be listening to some late Brahms.

33:01.040 --> 33:08.160
These are all things I like very much indeed, but, yes, I sometimes want something a bit lighter

33:08.160 --> 33:13.680
that's not unintelligent, but is entertaining and gives me a chance to relax a bit, and I

33:14.480 --> 33:20.000
never criticize anyone else for wanting to do the same. I would worry a lot if that's all

33:20.000 --> 33:29.120
there was in culture, and I think that's a very real worry to have, but I started asking myself

33:30.400 --> 33:37.200
a while ago, maybe at least 10 years ago, maybe even more, of a lot of the types of

33:37.200 --> 33:42.480
avant-garde music that I've played, how often do I choose to actually listen to them myself?

33:43.840 --> 33:50.400
And I mean, I certainly do, but not as often as one might think. I mean, when it's just listening,

33:50.400 --> 33:54.000
because I'm interested, rather than listening because I need to learn more about something,

33:54.000 --> 33:59.040
because I'm writing about it, or I'm listening to recordings in the process of preparing

33:59.120 --> 34:06.000
interpretation or something like that, but just listening, for pleasure doesn't seem quite the

34:06.000 --> 34:11.840
right way to put it, but listening for my own edification, I suppose, I've thought it's not

34:11.840 --> 34:17.920
actually all that often. And then I ask myself, similarly, how often do I listen to early music?

34:18.720 --> 34:24.000
Same here, or how often would I listen to even something like the Matas Passion?

34:24.880 --> 34:31.440
And they're for special occasions. I mean, there are times when I've got time,

34:31.440 --> 34:34.880
and I've got a clear head, and I really want to concentrate, and I really want something

34:35.520 --> 34:42.800
that goes as deep as those things are. And if you know, as someone who's quite intensely

34:42.800 --> 34:50.400
involved with these things as part of their work, if it's not so often that I get the chance to do

34:50.400 --> 34:58.240
that, then what's the chance for those working in other fields? Who don't have that? But from that,

34:58.240 --> 35:05.280
I still don't think that necessarily has to be a problem. I think there can be many forms of art,

35:06.400 --> 35:11.840
which are, let's go back to the first question, which are great, which are demanding,

35:13.440 --> 35:18.640
and which are not probably for casual or recreational viewing, listening, reading,

35:18.640 --> 35:26.000
or whatever. But I don't think that in any sense minimizes their significance or their importance.

35:28.160 --> 35:33.200
Well, if I could just continue one thing on that, because I want to look,

35:33.200 --> 35:39.360
I mean, the Eliot Carter example is interesting there. In a sense, I can see that I can view

35:39.360 --> 35:43.920
Carter's work, which I like very much, and I've played most of his piano music,

35:44.560 --> 35:48.320
is an extension of that. And Carter's work,

35:52.160 --> 35:59.600
if I say there's, in one small sense, it's slightly conservative. I don't mean that in any sort of

35:59.600 --> 36:04.800
denigratory fashion. I mean, in a sense, it's music that situates itself in a particular

36:04.800 --> 36:14.880
relationship to traditions, which I think is quite clear. It's not radically iconoclastic work,

36:14.880 --> 36:22.080
never has been, not in the way that certainly things like Cage or Schnabel or Globacar might be,

36:22.080 --> 36:27.920
not things that are really sort of trying to make you redefine the whole question of what music is.

36:27.920 --> 36:38.640
Carter's work uses an expressive language, which has a clear lineage behind it. He uses forms,

36:38.640 --> 36:47.360
which are certainly informed by his own particular means, not least on a metrical level, but on the

36:47.360 --> 36:54.160
other hand, they still somehow relate to established forms in things. And so that

36:54.160 --> 37:00.320
gives the point of reference. That gives, for those familiar with that tradition,

37:00.320 --> 37:05.680
you can hear it relative, listen to it relative to that tradition if you're familiar with that.

37:05.680 --> 37:09.920
And what that would mean to someone not familiar with that tradition is not necessarily so

37:11.120 --> 37:20.800
clear. But, and this is the question, like I think so many involved in new music, I've evaded

37:20.800 --> 37:29.120
for a long time, but I can't really get away from is simply about atonality. Now, if I define

37:29.120 --> 37:38.240
atonality as, or atonal music is music which is not organized around single tonal centers for any

37:38.240 --> 37:45.840
appreciable amount of time. I mean, I don't think there's almost any fully atonal music,

37:45.840 --> 37:50.560
music where you can't hear some localized tonal centers at various points, but they're so

37:50.560 --> 37:58.800
diffuse and so changing in atonal music as to essentially issue that sort of sense of

37:58.800 --> 38:03.440
some gravitational force such as a more long range tonal organization provides.

38:06.400 --> 38:14.960
Atonal music is disorienting. It is alienating, I think, to an awful lot of people. I mean,

38:14.960 --> 38:21.520
every bit of evidence points to that the lack of much of an atonal tradition in almost any other

38:21.520 --> 38:26.400
world culture. Perhaps you could find some, something akin in, say, gagaku music or so on,

38:27.200 --> 38:31.920
but it's not really comparable. I wonder about this. This is a question that I ask myself quite

38:31.920 --> 38:36.960
often as well. Now, I don't think I'm being self-deluding about this because obviously I write

38:36.960 --> 38:42.000
completely chromatic music and indeed sometimes infracromatic music with microtones and so on.

38:42.240 --> 38:47.600
My sense is, having worked with a lot of students and having exchanged with a very broad range of

38:47.600 --> 38:52.240
audience members through my public lecturing and through the work I've done as a composer as well,

38:52.240 --> 38:58.400
my sense is that the organization of the tones is not really at the forefront of most people's

38:58.400 --> 39:02.720
concerns when they're listening to things and finding them perhaps too esoteric or too difficult

39:02.720 --> 39:09.360
to handle. I think the absence of identifiable patterns in music is extremely challenging for

39:10.320 --> 39:15.440
audiences, but that can come through any means, actually. It's not simply a matter of the

39:15.440 --> 39:20.480
organization of tones. I think it may have to do somewhat with rhythm. I think that the

39:21.600 --> 39:28.320
tendency of the second Viennese school composers, for example, and certainly the generation that

39:28.320 --> 39:36.800
came after that, to work with rhythmic patterns that do not relate in any obvious manner to

39:37.760 --> 39:42.960
a meter, to a pattern, I think that that's more destabilizing than any degree of

39:45.920 --> 39:53.920
atonality in the music. There are so many examples of ostensibly tonal music that is so far into

39:53.920 --> 39:58.720
the margins of what constitutes any kind of functionality that it's difficult to make a

39:58.720 --> 40:05.360
case for the piece being in this or that key. For example, you can cite certain passages in

40:05.360 --> 40:10.400
Wagner, you can cite Hugo Woeuf, certainly, where it's extraordinarily difficult to determine

40:10.400 --> 40:15.520
if many of those songs are, in fact, in a key at all. You can cite Debussy, you can look at

40:16.720 --> 40:22.160
certain works by Hindemith, you can look at things like the Bagatelle Santonalité of Liszt.

40:24.240 --> 40:29.520
Those works don't seem to disturb anybody. Well, the Bagatelle Santonalité, I'd say, is in B minor.

40:29.760 --> 40:32.240
Okay. Well, that settles it.

40:34.400 --> 40:40.880
I think it's simply a piece that lacks a clear tonic in root position,

40:41.600 --> 40:47.280
rather than lacks a tonal center. There's a very, very clear tonal organization in that.

40:48.160 --> 40:54.000
It's nothing like the cutter drift in the way that Schoenberg from Op. 11 onwards is.

40:54.960 --> 41:00.000
And when you're talking about recognizable patterns, well, what about in Schoenberg's

41:00.000 --> 41:05.840
Suite Op. 25, or the Third String Quartet, or the Variations for Orchestra, do these not use a quite

41:07.200 --> 41:11.440
readily recognizable rhythmic vocabulary and gestural vocabulary as well?

41:11.920 --> 41:16.960
Which I thought, I mean, I've seen some fascinating talks about these works, which

41:17.760 --> 41:23.360
actually push the pitch organization to one side and look at them more primarily in gestural terms.

41:24.400 --> 41:28.880
And actually how subtle the gestural and rhythmic working is in them.

41:28.880 --> 41:37.120
And which, you know, which I find fascinating. It's a lot more than about what makes these,

41:37.120 --> 41:41.280
to my mind, quite remarkable pieces than just saying how the rose manipulated.

41:41.280 --> 41:44.880
But sorry, it's a little tangent here, but you might find it's quite interesting here that

41:46.160 --> 41:51.680
I was just in a conference at Dublin last week, and I was sort of supporting a postgraduate student

41:51.680 --> 41:58.720
who was giving a paper, which I had some input into. We're looking at the role of music theory

41:58.720 --> 42:05.120
analysis comparatively in Scottish and Irish educational systems and how this relates to

42:05.120 --> 42:11.520
secondary provision and so on. And one thing she found from talking to teachers in Scotland is they

42:11.520 --> 42:18.960
said, serialism is a gift for teaching, because it's not difficult for students to learn how to

42:18.960 --> 42:25.120
just invert and retrograde the row, and then just combine that and they create something in the process.

42:26.160 --> 42:30.720
Yeah, whether there's something you'd ever want to listen to is another question. But

42:31.760 --> 42:36.960
I mean, this to me portrays such a narrow understanding of what serial music is, and

42:36.960 --> 42:41.520
certainly what the serial music of Schoenberg or Berg or Webern is, that there are so many other

42:41.520 --> 42:48.480
aspects which are defining to what makes it so distinctive. It's not just about the row

42:48.560 --> 42:54.400
manipulation. And as we know, Schoenberg reacted quite negatively to Rudolf Kirlisch,

42:55.120 --> 42:58.640
coming back and saying, I've worked out this is how the row works in the third string quartet.

43:00.240 --> 43:06.400
So I suppose I'm saying from this that I'm not sure that those other factors that you think

43:06.400 --> 43:11.280
are probably more important for listeners than pitch organisation. I'm not sure if those things

43:11.840 --> 43:18.080
aren't present in a lot of these works, which nonetheless, have never gone on to have the

43:18.080 --> 43:26.720
same sustained and wide listenership that works of Stravinsky or Bartok or Prokofiev have. And

43:29.200 --> 43:35.840
I don't in any sense want to sort of suggest that those latter group composers are any less

43:35.920 --> 43:40.960
modern. In fact, in some sense is more so than the second Viennese school.

43:44.000 --> 43:47.760
And you could trace a different sort of history through the 20th century, which

43:48.880 --> 43:56.000
is certainly focused on lots of very innovative developments. I mean,

43:56.000 --> 44:03.440
was obviously with Debussy, as you mentioned, but which I don't believe ultimately give up on

44:03.440 --> 44:08.960
some form of tonal organisation. I don't believe Debussy does. We were saying about Wagner, Hugo

44:08.960 --> 44:15.840
Volf. I think for momentary periods, they go off directions, but I think it's still ultimately clear.

44:16.640 --> 44:18.640
I think even in Charles Ives, that's the case as well.

44:18.640 --> 44:23.120
Well, the harmony is fundamentally triadic in nature most of the time,

44:24.000 --> 44:29.520
even though it may not be obvious how the modulatory scheme works and how it might all

44:29.520 --> 44:36.560
relate to essential tonality. But something along those lines, having an extended tonality

44:36.560 --> 44:42.800
that is fundamentally centred around triads is probably, that might be the marker. But then

44:42.800 --> 44:47.120
again, it's very complicated. It's terribly difficult to parse it all out because a lot of

44:47.120 --> 44:51.120
the harmony in Opus 11 is triadic, if you look at the chords.

44:51.840 --> 45:01.680
But modified triads with added notes that sort of preclude them from fulfilling the

45:01.680 --> 45:06.720
usual triadic functions. Yes, but Scriabin, it's tricky, it's tricky.

45:07.280 --> 45:10.320
Yes, but it's more directional in Scriabin, I think.

45:11.360 --> 45:16.080
Depends. Some of those pieces are quite static in their harmonic effect, I would argue.

45:16.960 --> 45:20.240
I think of the opening of the eight sonata, for example.

45:22.880 --> 45:29.280
That's just a modified cadence in A, I think, for all the high amount of chromaticism.

45:30.160 --> 45:35.120
It's still got these basic cadential function working underneath it.

45:38.080 --> 45:41.120
Look at the beginning of the tenth sonata. It starts with essentially

45:41.600 --> 45:51.600
outlining an augmented triad on G-flat, and then that moves down to an E-flat minor triad.

45:54.400 --> 46:01.760
That to me is just a certain type of cadence from the third to the first degree of the scale,

46:02.720 --> 46:10.320
as in terms of the bass line, that it's not...

46:12.800 --> 46:20.080
Now, but then if I say look at one of the most tonal of Schoenberg's early A tonal works being

46:20.080 --> 46:31.360
the Opus 11 number two. So, for any listening to this who don't know this piece, it starts with an

46:31.440 --> 46:37.840
oscillating F and D in the bass and a lower F, an octave below the higher one,

46:39.040 --> 46:46.480
which could very simply imply a D minor harmony. But then when the melody comes above that,

46:46.480 --> 46:56.160
it's quite... It goes from D-flat to A, and then down a tri-tone to E-flat, and up a fourth to A-flat,

46:56.160 --> 47:02.880
and then back down a tri-tone to D. But inevitably that D naturalism here

47:02.880 --> 47:08.000
sounds to me like a resolution. And when I'm hearing the other chromatic notes,

47:08.000 --> 47:12.240
they're just implying a resolution that's going to come. Now Schoenberg does this,

47:12.240 --> 47:15.040
but sometimes he holds back or doesn't even resolve, but...

47:15.040 --> 47:20.240
No, clearly. Well, I would argue that that principle is operative to a greater or lesser

47:20.240 --> 47:25.440
degree in a lot of the works, where the E-flat sounds like a flat supertonic more or less.

47:25.440 --> 47:30.160
It's the same in the slow movement of the fourth quartet to a degree. It seems to have,

47:30.160 --> 47:36.240
which coincidentally also sounds like it's in D minor. So it's a question of degree,

47:36.240 --> 47:41.200
but I'm not convinced by the idea that that is the level on which these works are fundamentally

47:41.200 --> 47:47.200
challenging for audiences. It may have to do with the rate of change, with the constant

47:47.200 --> 47:52.800
onslaught of new chromatic pitches, the harmonic rhythm. The harmonic rhythm in the

47:52.800 --> 47:56.800
right of spring is drastically slowed down in comparison.

47:58.240 --> 48:03.920
And we know Schoenberg didn't like repetition, and this might be a key thing here.

48:06.240 --> 48:08.720
Yes, there's a sort of information overload.

48:08.720 --> 48:13.840
Well, if you take a work like De Stade by Andreessen, you have rhythmic patterns that are

48:13.840 --> 48:19.520
obvious and easy to hear. You have tonal patterns that are obvious and easy to hear. The harmonic

48:19.520 --> 48:26.400
rhythm is extremely slow. You have gestures and contrasts that form very clear and simple

48:26.400 --> 48:30.720
formal markers in the piece. It's hypnotic, it's repetitive, and so on.

48:33.120 --> 48:37.760
It's not obvious to me that De Stade is a more popular work than the fourth string quartet

48:37.760 --> 48:43.760
of Schoenberg. Maybe it is, but I don't know that that's the level on which... Do you see what I mean?

48:44.720 --> 48:54.640
It's tricky. I think we'd need some empirical data for this. We need to play some audiences,

48:55.360 --> 48:58.560
both the works, and then engage their responses to them.

49:01.200 --> 49:08.720
There might be some who are quite conservative listeners who think the Schoenberg sounds quite

49:09.200 --> 49:15.760
refined, and whereas I think the Andreessen's all a bit too noisy and riotous. That's very

49:15.760 --> 49:19.680
possible, but I think you could say the same about the Rite of Spring as well.

49:21.600 --> 49:27.200
Well, I tried an experiment with my students when I was teaching at the conservatory in Cambrai in

49:27.200 --> 49:31.600
northern France, and I had some younger students in that class. We were doing a course on musical

49:31.600 --> 49:38.320
analysis, and the idea was to alternate 20th century works with more established classical

49:38.320 --> 49:43.520
works. We were looking at late romanticism. We were looking at things like Wagner and

49:43.520 --> 49:48.640
Mahler and so on, and then one week I brought in the five orchestral pieces by Schoenberg,

49:49.280 --> 49:55.280
and we listened to them. To the students, it wasn't immediately obvious that the

49:56.720 --> 50:02.320
tonal organization of that work was in some fundamental manner all that different from

50:03.040 --> 50:09.280
a more chromatic example, say, from Liszt or Wagner. Now, that kind of surprised me. I wasn't

50:09.280 --> 50:14.240
expecting that reaction, but it was in fact repeated multiple times, and if I asked them to

50:14.240 --> 50:20.080
say, well, which work is tonal and which work is non-tonal, it wasn't necessarily categorically

50:20.080 --> 50:29.040
obvious to them. How well versed in the standard repertoire would those students have been?

50:30.000 --> 50:34.240
Well, they were younger, so presumably their exposure to the repertoire would have been

50:34.240 --> 50:39.520
limited, I imagine. They would have probably been centering themselves around a small number of

50:39.520 --> 50:42.800
works that they were attempting to master on their instruments. I don't get the sense that they would

50:42.800 --> 50:48.080
go home and listen to ten symphonies a day. So not really immersed in the tradition?

