probably the best known now is that in Dono Eshingen and later in Baden-Baden and Berlin,

01:14:54.160 --> 01:14:59.680
I've read enough about the reception of the concerts there, and wider commentary about

01:14:59.680 --> 01:15:04.240
festival culture to see many of the same sorts of sentiments being expressed then.

01:15:04.880 --> 01:15:13.360
A concern that new music was sort of painting itself into a corner was obsessed with certain

01:15:13.360 --> 01:15:18.720
types of experiment over and above the challenges of writing something that might have some

01:15:18.720 --> 01:15:25.600
wider currency. And, well, it's quite interesting if we look back at the programs from Dono Eshingen,

01:15:25.600 --> 01:15:33.760
I mean, how many Psytopias are known nowadays, whatever happened to those sort of radio

01:15:33.760 --> 01:15:42.320
compositions that people, including Hindemith wrote, or, I mean, actually many of the figures there,

01:15:42.320 --> 01:15:47.840
I mean, who listens to Heinz Teesson or Ernst Tocke, except perhaps the geographical fugue

01:15:48.480 --> 01:15:53.440
nowadays. Even a figure like Stefan Wolper is really very much a composer,

01:15:55.680 --> 01:16:00.480
appreciated within a narrow circle, but not that much outside of there. But you did see

01:16:00.480 --> 01:16:05.120
things like New Works of Bartok being played at these festivals as well, and those have made

01:16:05.120 --> 01:16:14.080
their way into some sort of wider repertoire. So, I am in time going to be writing a new

01:16:14.080 --> 01:16:19.600
history of musical modernism in the Weimar Republic, and it strikes me how little of the German

01:16:19.600 --> 01:16:25.600
composers of that time are heard with any frequency nowadays. Hindemith's reputation is nothing like

01:16:25.600 --> 01:16:33.200
it was when I was younger, let alone what it was in the 50s. Certainly the Second Vanity School are

01:16:33.200 --> 01:16:40.000
played, but even even that's within, I mean, I think probably most musicians have encountered

01:16:40.000 --> 01:16:44.480
some of their work, but it hasn't really etched you to wider currency. But that to one side,

01:16:44.480 --> 01:16:49.760
Kurt Vile's work has definitely had a lasting impression. You don't often hear that advanced

01:16:49.760 --> 01:16:56.240
Kronik nowadays. You don't hear Tach, you don't hear Ties, and you don't hear Max Butting.

01:16:58.240 --> 01:17:07.680
Any Phillips Janak, any number of other people who are really quite sort of prominent figures in

01:17:07.680 --> 01:17:17.040
the 20s and 30s in Germany are now pretty much forgotten. But maybe that's quite

01:17:17.120 --> 01:17:20.800
inevitable. I could think of any number of 19th century figures for whom the same could be

01:17:21.440 --> 01:17:27.200
said. Maybe if just a few things come out of this festival circuit and go on to continue

01:17:27.200 --> 01:17:33.680
to be listened to, that in itself is as much as we might reasonably hope for. So, it might be a bit

01:17:33.680 --> 01:17:40.960
premature to say that what's being played in the new music infrastructure is a term I like to use

01:17:40.960 --> 01:17:47.120
for it, the network of festivals, of concert series, of radio stations and programmes,

01:17:47.840 --> 01:17:53.040
and some educational institutions and journals and things as well. What is known in that,

01:17:53.920 --> 01:18:00.160
to say that it has little wider currency, doesn't register outside of that, may not be so new, and

01:18:01.040 --> 01:18:06.320
I think we shouldn't wholly rule out the possibility that might be a few things that do.

01:18:06.320 --> 01:18:11.520
That's the first point, but my other points might sort of slightly temper that.

01:18:12.960 --> 01:18:23.040
The second point I really think is important to bear in mind. When you compare music with

01:18:23.040 --> 01:18:30.480
other cultural forms, with literature, with the visual arts, with film and television,

01:18:31.440 --> 01:18:40.480
with dance as well, and theatre, I don't think in any of the others is quite as much of a chasm

01:18:40.480 --> 01:18:45.680
between the popular and the high art form as exists in music.

01:18:47.360 --> 01:18:49.280
You can trace that back to Wagner, if not earlier.

01:18:50.080 --> 01:18:55.840
Yes, certainly, but I think it's become especially pronounced in the 20th century.

01:18:56.800 --> 01:19:03.520
That, I mean, what perhaps hasn't really existed on any sustained, 20 sustained degree

01:19:04.240 --> 01:19:11.760
since figures like Britain and Shostakovich say is, or Kalamides Hartman would be another,

01:19:12.720 --> 01:19:16.480
is a sustained tradition of music which somehow,

01:19:19.920 --> 01:19:23.200
I don't want, I really don't want to use the term middle brow because I dislike it.

01:19:23.200 --> 01:19:27.840
I don't think that's a very fair term for those composers. I don't think those composers are any

01:19:27.840 --> 01:19:33.920
less sort of serious or any less demanding than some of their more avant-garde counterpoints.

01:19:34.720 --> 01:19:39.600
But they are working comfortably from within a tradition without

01:19:41.680 --> 01:19:48.400
engaging any sort of radically iconoclastic activity there. And as such, it's not such a leap

01:19:48.400 --> 01:19:53.920
from an interest in that tradition to an interest in their work.

01:19:53.920 --> 01:20:00.080
Well, you might be able to cite figures such as John Adams, for example, Philip Glass perhaps,

01:20:01.200 --> 01:20:06.640
to a limited degree, George Benjamin, although I would situate him much more in the new music

01:20:06.640 --> 01:20:11.360
realm than anything resembling what Benjamin Britton achieved.

01:20:12.400 --> 01:20:16.000
Which is, of course, not a commentary on the achievement of George Benjamin, but simply to

01:20:16.000 --> 01:20:23.200
point out that he doesn't have that level of cultural penetration or of accessibility in his

01:20:23.200 --> 01:20:29.440
work. But then you could say, well, the counterargument could say, well, yes, but a figure such as

01:20:29.440 --> 01:20:36.880
Glass, for example, is not as compositionally accomplished. The music is not of as high quality

01:20:36.880 --> 01:20:45.600
as a lot of the output of Britton. And it's tricky to find any kind of figure

01:20:46.560 --> 01:20:52.160
who would be who would be comparable or analogous in any way whatsoever to someone like that,

01:20:52.160 --> 01:20:54.320
I would argue. Well, Satie, perhaps.

01:20:56.000 --> 01:20:57.600
Satie? Why so?

01:20:59.600 --> 01:21:08.960
Using very sort of limited and delimited compositional resources towards a particular end.

01:21:10.560 --> 01:21:14.320
I mean, in terms of what you're saying, Glass being less accomplished as a composer than

01:21:14.320 --> 01:21:16.880
Britton. I'm not making that argument. I'm sorry.

01:21:16.880 --> 01:21:18.240
It's a devil's advocate position.

01:21:18.240 --> 01:21:23.360
Yeah, because I'm not sure that would be easy to justify as an argument.

01:21:25.520 --> 01:21:31.120
I mean, we could say that a large amount of Morton Feldman's music is quiet,

01:21:31.120 --> 01:21:34.960
so he showed he could write quiet music, but he wasn't so good at the mezzo-forte as a fortissimo.

01:21:34.960 --> 01:21:39.760
But that would be a really facile argument. I think because some composers have

01:21:40.720 --> 01:21:46.640
stuck within limited realms doesn't make them any less accomplished than those who've done

01:21:46.640 --> 01:21:51.040
broader things. I mean, I know Schrockhausen once criticized composer, and it's thought he

01:21:51.040 --> 01:21:55.200
might have had people like Ligeti or Zanakis or Feldman in mind, who said, if you want to make

01:21:55.200 --> 01:22:01.200
a big name, do something like become the snare drum composer. That's in the Robin McConae book.

01:22:03.520 --> 01:22:08.880
So, okay, now I appreciate you saying that as a devil's advocate argument rather than

01:22:08.960 --> 01:22:14.480
as your own one. And I think it is true to say that Glass and Adam's iteration,

01:22:14.480 --> 01:22:20.880
others have achieved a genuine penetration to a wider public sphere in some ways,

01:22:20.880 --> 01:22:30.400
perhaps more so than some more canonical figures. But that's a very particular direction,

01:22:30.400 --> 01:22:36.160
and it's not one I want to denigrate by any means. I might have harsher things to say

01:22:36.880 --> 01:22:39.600
about some of the propaganda surrounding it, whether coming from

01:22:40.320 --> 01:22:44.960
composers or their advocates, and also about the historiography which I've written about,

01:22:45.760 --> 01:22:51.360
which sort of posits that everything was going to pot in new music, and then these people came

01:22:51.360 --> 01:22:57.120
along and saved their, saved its ass, as it were. And I dislike that sort of rhetoric,

01:22:57.200 --> 01:23:04.480
even expressed in slightly less crude terms. But I think that work stands

01:23:07.200 --> 01:23:12.080
quite outside of the classical tradition in many ways.

01:23:12.080 --> 01:23:18.560
Well, Feldman characterized it as showbiz. He was saying he doesn't take Filt Glass seriously,

01:23:18.560 --> 01:23:22.800
because he's in showbiz. He's not a composer, which, you know, you don't have to take that

01:23:22.800 --> 01:23:26.640
seriously as a remark, but... Well, some Kurt Wallin showbiz, very literally.

01:23:27.920 --> 01:23:31.840
And I'd say he's a very serious composer, and I don't just mean his early works, I mean,

01:23:31.840 --> 01:23:33.920
all the way up to his American musicals.

01:23:39.760 --> 01:23:45.600
When I wrote my big two-part article on the historiography of minimal music, I posited that

01:23:46.480 --> 01:23:53.920
there are three, because I don't think minimal music represents a drastic break.

01:23:53.920 --> 01:23:58.240
I think it does represent a break with a lot of Central European traditions,

01:23:58.240 --> 01:24:02.960
but it has a clear lineage, and it's sort of one branch coming out of several roots.

01:24:02.960 --> 01:24:08.240
And those roots include Musica Sati, above all, the earlier music of Stravinsky,

01:24:08.240 --> 01:24:15.120
especially of Lesacre and Lenos. And then, and this is the argument that comes out of

01:24:16.320 --> 01:24:21.280
work of Wim Mertens, who wrote one of the early books on minimal music, that it actually comes

01:24:21.280 --> 01:24:28.000
out of integral serialism, in a way, and the figure of Hoivetz, who bridges those two worlds,

01:24:28.000 --> 01:24:34.640
demonstrates that. Also, the fact that Lamont Young's early work can be seen like a sort of

01:24:34.640 --> 01:24:41.840
expansion of Feldman onto a vast, expansion of Weber, onto a vast canvas as well.

01:24:43.520 --> 01:24:50.400
That relationship is more complex and difficult. But then, within the traditions bequeased by

01:24:50.400 --> 01:24:55.520
those roots, I would include Feldman's music, or Christian Wolf's music on one hand. I would include,

01:24:56.480 --> 01:25:03.120
say, some of the work of Nicholas Ahuba, or Ernst Albrecht Stiebler, using very limited resources,

01:25:03.120 --> 01:25:07.920
or some aspects of music spectral as well. All those different branches coming out of

01:25:09.120 --> 01:25:17.520
a fundamental aesthetic of relative stasis, which rejects this particular dynamic and

01:25:17.520 --> 01:25:21.600
dialectical approach to composition. Well, there's an interesting article, actually,

01:25:21.600 --> 01:25:27.200
by Jonathan Harvey that deals with that topic. And his contention is that this is the inevitable

01:25:27.200 --> 01:25:33.120
heritage of the Weberian project, which is of having a harmony that's completely unmoored

01:25:33.120 --> 01:25:37.360
from any kind of a base function. Or rather, as he puts it, the base has moved up into the

01:25:37.360 --> 01:25:41.680
middle register, but it's no longer determining the harmony. I think that was published in

01:25:41.680 --> 01:25:47.840
contact. You probably have read that article. And that, in consequence, because of this absence of

01:25:47.840 --> 01:25:53.760
gravity, so to speak, in the harmony, then it forces you, in a sense, to have a

01:25:54.480 --> 01:26:01.680
a significantly slowed down harmonic rhythm. And that leads to, or to a stasis of some kind,

01:26:01.680 --> 01:26:07.680
effectively. The music no longer is oriented or grounded. And that leads you to things like

01:26:07.680 --> 01:26:10.480
the Feldman pieces. But that's not the only example.

01:26:10.480 --> 01:26:18.400
I could trace that sort of unanchored music, if you like, that horizontally focused music

01:26:19.040 --> 01:26:25.680
back to such things as the publications of books on linear counterpoint by Ernst Kurt in

01:26:25.680 --> 01:26:35.520
1917. And the whole new lease of life that that sort of thought gave to a music that was

01:26:35.520 --> 01:26:44.400
about line rather than about harmony as well. That's before some of Weber's major essays in

01:26:44.400 --> 01:26:51.200
that sort of genre. But that's that sort of thinking, which is, on one hand, radical,

01:26:51.200 --> 01:26:56.000
on the other hand, quite conservative, because it's really looking back to a time before the

01:26:56.000 --> 01:27:01.680
19th century, before harmony comes to sort of take precedence over counterpoint and harmony

01:27:01.680 --> 01:27:06.800
comes to be taught first towards an idea that counterpoint is at the root of things and harmony

01:27:06.800 --> 01:27:14.240
is at most a byproduct of that. But it's using that to a radical end towards the construction

01:27:14.240 --> 01:27:20.880
of music, which isn't sort of formed around some tonal principles, which you can still say

01:27:20.880 --> 01:27:25.280
of relatively modal counterpoint, at least in the equal temperament era.

01:27:25.280 --> 01:27:31.120
Okay, you seem to be arguing in that the points that I've raised in terms of how

01:27:31.120 --> 01:27:36.960
the present moment in terms of musical production seems to me to be fundamentally

01:27:37.600 --> 01:27:43.360
different from the way it would have been 50 or 60 years ago. That's not even to go back

01:27:43.360 --> 01:27:48.560
any farther than that. You seem to be arguing that for many of the points that I'm raising,

01:27:48.560 --> 01:27:52.000
there are historical precedents for it, there is a degree of connectedness,

01:27:52.000 --> 01:27:56.000
there's nothing fundamentally exceptional about the present moment.

01:27:56.000 --> 01:28:00.800
No, I wouldn't quite say that. I think there are differences to the present moment that I was

01:28:00.800 --> 01:28:07.840
coming on to when I mentioned about sort of the relationship to popular music, which is something

01:28:07.840 --> 01:28:15.360
I would loosely trace back to the early 19th century. It's an urban music fundamentally

01:28:15.360 --> 01:28:22.320
associated with the growth of larger cities and so on. And it takes forms of things such as Music Hall

01:28:22.320 --> 01:28:29.280
or Cafe Conceal, Cabaret or Vorderville in the 19th century, then through traditions of ragtime,

01:28:29.280 --> 01:28:37.360
blues and early jazz and so on. But it really comes together, I think I would say in the 40s,

01:28:37.360 --> 01:28:42.880
rather than the mid 50s, mid 50s is commonly the date given for the beginning of rock and roll.

01:28:42.880 --> 01:28:47.760
But I would say it comes together with the beginning of Rhythm and Blues as a really

01:28:47.760 --> 01:28:53.440
established genre in New Orleans at the beginning of the 40s, which is exactly the point that Fats

01:28:53.440 --> 01:29:00.560
Domino was very keen to point out to some interviewer who asked him in the mid 50s,

01:29:00.560 --> 01:29:03.120
tell me about this new music called Rock and Roll Your Play. He says,

01:29:03.120 --> 01:29:06.240
I call it Rhythm and Blues and I've been playing it in New Orleans since 1940.

01:29:07.360 --> 01:29:13.040
So I think it's around that time that something really comes together that forms a truly lasting

01:29:13.040 --> 01:29:20.320
tradition which gains a very wide currency and even a global currency in time to come.

01:29:21.440 --> 01:29:31.760
And that's a huge thing for an art music tradition to compete with. And I think more so than

01:29:31.760 --> 01:29:41.920
let's say literary fiction does with, compared to popular fiction. The chasm is not so great

01:29:41.920 --> 01:29:50.080
between them. Perhaps if we were talking only about that literature, the producer makes radical

01:29:50.080 --> 01:29:55.840
experiments with form, for example, say, well, some of the literature of Samuel Beckett, the work of

01:29:55.840 --> 01:30:04.000
B. S. Johnson, or figures like Eva Figus or Christine Brooke Rose or that sort of thing.

01:30:04.000 --> 01:30:14.080
There, that's probably about as far away from popular fiction as you could get.

01:30:14.080 --> 01:30:20.160
Same in cinema. If you were looking at a very experimental film, what, of Stan Brackage or

01:30:20.160 --> 01:30:25.520
Bill Viola or something like that and you were to compare that with Jurassic Park, then

01:30:25.600 --> 01:30:33.760
there's a big chasm. But if you'd compare, say, the very intelligent films but made for a mainstream

01:30:33.760 --> 01:30:39.680
audience like, say, those of Martin Scorsese with some of the more populous inclined things of George

01:30:39.680 --> 01:30:44.800
Lucas and Steven Spielberg, I don't think there's anything like the same sort of total

01:30:46.080 --> 01:30:52.320
difference of intent and means and everything there. But that's, it's very hard for me to think

01:30:52.320 --> 01:30:59.680
of a composer who's equivalent to someone like Scorsese in cinema. And that's in no sense to call

01:30:59.680 --> 01:31:04.480
Scorsese a middle brow filmmaker. I think he's a very, very great filmmaker throughout his career.

01:31:05.520 --> 01:31:13.360
But he has worked within basically narrative oriented structures. He's done very imaginative

01:31:13.360 --> 01:31:20.400
things with all aspects of the cinema, all aspects of how you use cuts, how you use edits of other

01:31:20.400 --> 01:31:25.760
types, how you use the camera work, everything like that, how you use music actually, everything

01:31:25.760 --> 01:31:31.440
like that. But in ways that are meaningful to a mainstream audience.

01:31:32.000 --> 01:31:36.480
I think you'd have to look in the popular music sphere to find an equivalent figure. I don't

01:31:36.480 --> 01:31:41.280
think you'd find it in the composition world. Yeah. So maybe in the jazz sphere, something like

01:31:41.280 --> 01:31:48.640
Coltrane's A Love Supreme might be comparable in a way that something like Cecil Taylor's

01:31:48.640 --> 01:31:56.800
unit structures wouldn't, I think. If that makes sense. So I think

01:31:59.120 --> 01:32:07.520
the competition from popular culture is of a different order of magnitude. I mean, also just

01:32:07.520 --> 01:32:13.280
simply the global reach of it. I mean, does that much popular fiction other than perhaps

01:32:13.360 --> 01:32:17.680
J.K. Rowling and a few others, when she was more in vogue than she is now,

01:32:18.880 --> 01:32:25.280
how much popular fiction gets a truly, maybe 10 round as well, gets a truly global audience,

01:32:25.280 --> 01:32:31.280
like you could say of a quite a significant amount of popular music as well, probably even less so

01:32:31.280 --> 01:32:39.680
with theatre as well. So and, you know, a thing I noticed in academia, you can, when you talk about

01:32:39.680 --> 01:32:49.360
cultured people, again, I come across people who know huge amounts about literature, huge amounts

01:32:49.360 --> 01:32:54.560
about society and politics, lots about the visual arts, but you mentioned something like a D major

01:32:54.560 --> 01:32:59.200
scale to them. And they really think this is, you know, you might as well be talking about

01:32:59.200 --> 01:33:04.240
sort of advanced astrophysics. Right, right. But I don't think that would have been the case.

01:33:04.240 --> 01:33:09.520
And this was my third point. I don't think that would have been the case 30 or 40 years

01:33:09.520 --> 01:33:18.960
ago. I think a lot of educated people would have had some exposure to at least some basics of music

01:33:18.960 --> 01:33:25.360
theory and some basics of a Western classical musical tradition. And that's, that is disappearing,

01:33:25.360 --> 01:33:31.440
I think. It's particularly bad here in Britain and particularly bad in the US. But from all I can

01:33:31.440 --> 01:33:37.040
tell, it's sort of being marginalised out in lots of other countries as well, perhaps at a slightly

01:33:37.040 --> 01:33:48.080
different rate. And one of the consequences of this is that I'm, well, I think, I still think

01:33:48.640 --> 01:33:55.920
even some of the most radical work in new music, in some sense, has meaning relative to a tradition,

01:33:56.560 --> 01:34:00.800
including some of that stuff like Helmut Lachemann on where it's your cargo, and the sense is

01:34:00.800 --> 01:34:06.000
turning that tradition on its head. But you need to know what that tradition is to recognise it

01:34:06.000 --> 01:34:17.040
being turned on its head. The, I've heard from regularly, perhaps a bit too often from young

01:34:17.040 --> 01:34:24.240
composers, they think that the classical tradition is dead, or they want it to be dead, perhaps.

01:34:24.240 --> 01:34:29.280
I mean, in some universities, I think they don't want to have their own music to compete with that

01:34:29.280 --> 01:34:36.080
for student interest and favour. But some of some contemporary composers have played an active

01:34:37.520 --> 01:34:43.680
role in trying to sort of push that Western classical tradition out of the curriculum,

01:34:44.720 --> 01:34:47.200
in a way that I think is often very destructive.

01:34:47.200 --> 01:34:49.280
What do you think is their motivation for doing that?

01:34:49.280 --> 01:34:53.920
Well, as I say, on one hand, I think they want to have the ground to themselves for a certain sort of

01:34:54.880 --> 01:35:01.440
art music, if you like. And if they're just one composer amongst the great many spanning

01:35:01.440 --> 01:35:04.880
centuries, and they're a much smaller fish, and a much bigger pond.

01:35:04.880 --> 01:35:09.600
Do you think there are contemporary authors who are anxious about having their work

01:35:10.240 --> 01:35:11.360
compete with Shakespeare?

01:35:12.560 --> 01:35:13.600
Not to the same extent.

01:35:16.320 --> 01:35:20.960
Because composers routinely, I know this because I have, I work with so many students,

01:35:21.680 --> 01:35:27.280
they imagine themselves as being potentially in the same room as Beethoven, and they're not

01:35:27.280 --> 01:35:32.720
measuring up. But I don't see a lot of poets thinking now, hang on a minute, this is not as

01:35:32.720 --> 01:35:34.080
good as the Shakespearean sonnets.

01:35:35.360 --> 01:35:42.000
Well, because I think there is an audience for contemporary literature, I say, not the most

01:35:42.000 --> 01:35:48.080
radical experimental stuff I was mentioning, but a lot of artistic literature, if you like,

01:35:48.480 --> 01:35:56.240
which is not in its own right, which doesn't necessarily, those who read it don't necessarily

01:35:56.240 --> 01:36:02.960
have the same amount invested in at least sort of classics from before the 19th century.

01:36:03.760 --> 01:36:07.920
That's possible, I think the same is true in theatre as well, and possibly in the visual

01:36:07.920 --> 01:36:16.400
arts, so it's a bit more complex. I've not yet seen evidence that the same is true for new music.

01:36:17.360 --> 01:36:24.160
There's a few people, there's a few people who might like some progressive rock and some zapper

01:36:24.160 --> 01:36:27.920
or something, and then come from that into Stockhouse, and yes, I've known that happened,

01:36:27.920 --> 01:36:32.720
but I think that's quite exceptional. There isn't the same,

01:36:35.520 --> 01:36:41.440
constituency has say many who might read a novel of Martin Amos or something, or

01:36:41.520 --> 01:36:48.480
Michel Huelbeck, but wouldn't necessarily be that drawn to reading Daniel Defoe or reading

01:36:48.480 --> 01:36:59.520
Samantha's. I don't think that's there, or I haven't seen it in music, and so when I'm saying

01:36:59.520 --> 01:37:06.640
about those in universities who are pushing the sort of, take the dead white European males off

01:37:06.640 --> 01:37:12.000
the curriculum, and there are plenty of these, I think they're ultimately to some extent digging

01:37:12.000 --> 01:37:18.720
their own grave here, because if they- Well, the second part of that means get rid of the

01:37:18.720 --> 01:37:24.320
dead white males in order to make room for me. Yes, exactly, and sometimes it's just living

01:37:24.320 --> 01:37:28.480
white males. The only way they differ is they're not dead, but unfortunately we all will be in

01:37:28.480 --> 01:37:33.840
the end. Which posits that there's a zero-sum game effectively. Yes, there is.

01:37:36.320 --> 01:37:42.640
But if, I mean, I really wish some contemporary poets would think more about this, if you didn't have

01:37:44.160 --> 01:37:50.640
some sort of weight of tradition, which in some sense informs and gives somewhere to locate your

01:37:50.640 --> 01:37:55.760
work, if you're actually just having to compete on its own terms with popular music,

01:37:56.560 --> 01:38:04.240
do you think it was your standard chance? I hear lots of stuff about saying, oh,

01:38:04.240 --> 01:38:08.240
we have different modes of distribution, now anyone can produce things on a laptop, and you

01:38:08.240 --> 01:38:12.480
can produce a lot with a laptop, especially now with some of the latest AI software for

01:38:12.480 --> 01:38:18.480
composition, which I've looked at and has other sorts of new implications. There is a lot you

01:38:18.480 --> 01:38:26.160
can do in that respect, but how do you get anyone to listen to it? Anyone can do something,

01:38:26.160 --> 01:38:32.400
put it out on SoundCloud, or Spotify, or something like that. But that's just as true of popular

01:38:32.960 --> 01:38:39.920
genres as it is. Oh yes, sure. It's not as though it's any easier to emerge from nothing

01:38:39.920 --> 01:38:45.440
and make a gigantic career for yourself as a singer-songwriter. Oh, I know, and all

01:38:45.520 --> 01:38:50.560
I hear is this is getting harder and harder in the popular field to make any sort of impact

01:38:51.200 --> 01:38:56.080
when there are so many other people trying to do it, and there might be all sorts of factors

01:38:56.080 --> 01:39:01.600
with the small number who come from this and actually gain some sort of wider recognition,

01:39:01.600 --> 01:39:09.200
which is why it's a huge mistake. And it's disingenuous when you get things like Degreak

01:39:09.200 --> 01:39:14.880
or Supromasis to think, if you study popular music, that this will give you a route towards a great

01:39:15.760 --> 01:39:21.440
well-paying career. For everyone you see, every population you see who is doing that,

01:39:21.440 --> 01:39:26.160
there are any number of others who've done a handful of gigs and small venues and then

01:39:26.160 --> 01:39:34.320
just sort of split up. Nevertheless, my intuitive sense, having been in the new music world,

01:39:34.320 --> 01:39:39.920
I'm not really sure if I'm in it anymore, but perhaps I am, it's hard to say, is that

01:39:40.800 --> 01:39:48.800
that there's something either fundamentally broken or exhausted about that culture today.

01:39:49.520 --> 01:39:54.320
I don't know which. I don't know if it's repairable. I don't know if it ought to be repaired,

01:39:54.960 --> 01:40:02.480
but the sense I get attending concerts, and this could partly be a reflection of

01:40:02.480 --> 01:40:07.520
my being a little bit older now. So, of course, it feels different to attend a concert when you're

01:40:07.520 --> 01:40:12.480
42, as I am now, as opposed to when you're 22. The excitement level is perhaps not the same,

01:40:12.480 --> 01:40:18.480
because you've seen several hundred concerts in the intervening years. But it certainly seems to

01:40:18.480 --> 01:40:24.160
me, as though something has changed, there's much less of a sense of anticipation or excitement

01:40:24.160 --> 01:40:29.840
surrounding these events. There's a sense that the infrastructures that are supporting these sorts

01:40:29.840 --> 01:40:39.360
of events is on very shaky ground, I would say, that it may not be able to convincingly justify

01:40:39.360 --> 01:40:46.160
its own indefinite existence without some kind of massive change in the way that it's set up,

01:40:47.840 --> 01:40:54.320
and that we cannot indefinitely push off into the future the question of, well, who's listening to

01:40:54.400 --> 01:40:57.360
it? Well, future audiences, well, that doesn't work forever.

01:40:58.080 --> 01:41:04.800
No, it doesn't work forever. And then I'll just finish this with one more point. So, there are

01:41:04.800 --> 01:41:12.240
pieces that I've heard that involve enormous orchestras playing extraordinarily esoteric

01:41:12.240 --> 01:41:17.680
techniques that require a great deal of specialized training that is not something you can count on

01:41:17.680 --> 01:41:22.160
with the vast majority of professional orchestras. You need a specialized new music orchestra to do

01:41:22.160 --> 01:41:27.440
that. Specialized new music orchestras are, of course, financially non-viable, unless they're

01:41:27.440 --> 01:41:34.480
being massively subsidized by the state. These works require enormously expensive rehearsals to

01:41:34.480 --> 01:41:40.640
produce, and they're typically played once. And this is not by any means an isolated phenomenon.

01:41:40.640 --> 01:41:45.840
It is, in fact, the standard mode of operating for most of the continental festivals. And the

01:41:45.840 --> 01:41:53.440
assumption seems to be that it's better to program only premieres or buy-in-large premieres,

01:41:53.440 --> 01:41:59.680
let's say 90% of the works will be premieres. And it seems to be almost a structural phenomenon

01:42:00.480 --> 01:42:06.720
that, of course, these works won't be played again, or maybe they'll be dug up in 25 years

01:42:06.720 --> 01:42:13.280
and dusted off. But in the vast majority of cases, works that cost hundreds of thousands

01:42:13.360 --> 01:42:19.280
of euros to put on, there's no way that you can play them with anything like the frequency that

01:42:19.280 --> 01:42:24.160
would be required for them to become either familiar or to make any kind of an impression

01:42:24.160 --> 01:42:29.760
beyond the local audience of maybe a few hundred people that hears the premiere. So that, I think,

01:42:31.040 --> 01:42:36.320
I think that's got to stop, or it simply will stop out of its own inertia and out of the

01:42:36.320 --> 01:42:42.720
sheer financial absurdity of it. So if you were to compare something like that, a composition that

01:42:42.720 --> 01:42:48.560
takes two years to write, that requires a colossal budget in order to perform, and that can only

01:42:48.560 --> 01:42:56.240
be done once, that sounds to me like a non-starter. Compare that to a figure such as Vivian Meyer

01:42:56.240 --> 01:43:01.760
in the photography world. There we go. Vivian Meyer was a photographer who operated essentially

01:43:01.760 --> 01:43:09.760
in secret. She was a street photographer in Chicago who, for decades, took square format images

01:43:10.320 --> 01:43:15.200
with a rolloflex camera on the streets of Chicago, produced something like 25,000 photographs,

01:43:15.200 --> 01:43:18.960
just one of the finest street photographers of all time, never showed her work to anybody,

01:43:18.960 --> 01:43:23.920
never told anyone she was doing it. And when she died, all of these boxes of negatives were

01:43:23.920 --> 01:43:30.160
discovered by a film historian, and she became posthumously a phenomenon. But this work is done

01:43:30.160 --> 01:43:38.000
privately at no cost to anybody except the cost of a film for her, and ends up having a very

01:43:38.000 --> 01:43:44.800
significant popular impact when it's eventually discovered. So there's a colossal asymmetry

01:43:44.800 --> 01:43:50.080
between the means required to produce these things versus the number of people that will

01:43:50.080 --> 01:43:55.840
actually benefit from that. Well, I think we do have to distinguish between the performing and

01:43:55.840 --> 01:44:01.920
non-performing arts in this respect. I mean, photography can essentially be done by a single

01:44:01.920 --> 01:44:06.800
person. I recognize sometimes you have other people doing prints and the negatives and so on,

01:44:06.800 --> 01:44:12.880
but you don't require the whole apparatus of a group of performers to produce photography. It's

01:44:12.880 --> 01:44:24.160
the same story for literature as well. Whereas music or film or theater or dance are multi-person

01:44:24.160 --> 01:44:30.560
activities, and that's always going to be more expensive. And this is one reason why I say

01:44:31.200 --> 01:44:35.680
what some people say about, well, why can't the modern music world be like the modern art world,

01:44:35.680 --> 01:44:41.920
particularly in terms of the amounts of money that are made by some of the artists. But they

01:44:41.920 --> 01:44:50.320
produce a particular thing that becomes a commodity. But here's the thing. In the popular sphere,

01:44:51.040 --> 01:44:57.280
the amount of money that it costs to produce the thing is scaled in terms of the number of people

01:44:57.280 --> 01:45:02.320
that it can potentially reach. There's a coherence between those two things. So if you make a film

01:45:02.320 --> 01:45:07.200
that has a £100 million budget, for example, then you're expecting to get a return on that.

01:45:07.200 --> 01:45:13.040
You're expecting that it will draw at least £100 million in the box office. So you could argue,

01:45:13.040 --> 01:45:19.680
well, there's no reason why that should apply to the fine arts. But somebody does have to pay for

01:45:19.680 --> 01:45:26.960
it. There's no way to get around that fact. This is what I've been banging on about for years,

01:45:27.600 --> 01:45:34.640
a bit like a broken record, that I think the possible decline of a subsidy culture for new

01:45:34.640 --> 01:45:40.560
music is one of the biggest threats it could possibly face. There is no way that the vast

01:45:40.560 --> 01:45:45.600
majority of new music, other than things like rice and glass and a few others,

01:45:47.280 --> 01:45:52.640
could survive just on the open marketplace. The costs are too great and the returns too low.

01:45:53.600 --> 01:46:00.800
The listenership is too low, except for the odd few things that may... I mean, it's possible

01:46:00.800 --> 01:46:06.640
some orchestra could put a big bird whistle piece on within, in the context of an otherwise

01:46:07.280 --> 01:46:12.080
more traditional program, and they'd still get enough people in that that would just about cover

01:46:12.080 --> 01:46:18.800
the costs of it. But those cases... Well, and yes, with things like chamber music as well and solo

01:46:18.880 --> 01:46:24.000
performance where the costs aren't quite so great, it's also possible. But on the whole,

01:46:25.520 --> 01:46:31.440
the vast majority of new music, as we understand it, at least in European terms,

01:46:32.320 --> 01:46:40.160
only gets to be performed, only gets to be recorded through support, through state subsidies. So,

01:46:40.160 --> 01:46:45.840
money collected through taxation and redistributed to make up for the shortfall, or through the

01:46:45.840 --> 01:46:52.480
radio stations, or other broadcasters who collect it through the license fee, or to some extent

01:46:52.480 --> 01:47:02.800
through the universities as well. Now, I mean, certainly in Britain, we've seen sweeping cuts

01:47:02.800 --> 01:47:06.720
to arts funding, especially to music funding recently, the most prominent of which,

01:47:07.360 --> 01:47:14.080
Relitia English National Opera, which at the time we're talking, the idea is it could be relocated

01:47:14.080 --> 01:47:19.280
in Manchester, but it almost certainly won't be the same sort of entity that it was before.

01:47:21.120 --> 01:47:26.560
Big grant losses to things like the Britain symphony, to the London symphony, to the

01:47:26.560 --> 01:47:32.720
ensemble saffron in Manchester who have had to close down, and so on and so forth. And in economically

01:47:32.720 --> 01:47:40.640
difficult times, these things are seen as perhaps not the most pressing social needs, and some of

01:47:40.640 --> 01:47:47.360
the easiest things to cut when cuts are made. Now, many have said to me, why are you always so

01:47:47.360 --> 01:47:51.200
concerned? Why are you always talking about subsidy? And they don't want to talk about it. They don't

01:47:51.200 --> 01:47:56.720
think it's a very interesting issue or something. I say, well, you think it's all fine, doesn't

01:47:56.720 --> 01:48:02.720
need thinking about while it's there. But the moment, I say, the moment people start saying,

01:48:02.720 --> 01:48:06.800
well, maybe we don't need to spend this money on these ensembles, on these festivals,

01:48:06.880 --> 01:48:12.880
what will be the arguments you will use to try and oppose those cuts?

01:48:12.880 --> 01:48:19.040
Well, the problem is, that's exactly it. I don't think there necessarily are convincing

01:48:19.040 --> 01:48:22.480
arguments, at least not to the people that would be in charge of dispensing the funds.

01:48:23.040 --> 01:48:28.720
So for instance, you may have seen there's a rather well-known video on YouTube of Boulez

01:48:29.440 --> 01:48:34.880
on a talk show with, I think it's Michel Schneider, who is a French minister of the time,

01:48:35.440 --> 01:48:40.640
who gets rather combative with Boulez. And they're talking about Irkheim. And he says, well,

01:48:41.920 --> 01:48:46.640
Irkheim is costing, I don't remember the figure, it was a colossal amount of money. It's costing

01:48:47.360 --> 01:48:53.920
a significant percentage of the budget, the annual budget for music from the Ministry of Culture.

01:48:54.720 --> 01:48:59.920
And the minister was basically asking Boulez, how can you possibly justify the expense of an

01:48:59.920 --> 01:49:06.480
institution like this, given the extremely small amount of productions that it's actually producing

01:49:06.480 --> 01:49:11.440
in terms of public concerts, in terms of anything that anybody in the general public could possibly

01:49:11.440 --> 01:49:16.800
either understand or could attend. And of course, Boulez gets very angry and defensive and calls

01:49:16.800 --> 01:49:22.400
the minister a fraud. But he basically sidesteps the question. He's very defensive, very angry,

01:49:23.280 --> 01:49:28.960
but he doesn't acknowledge that there may be somewhere in there a totally legitimate question,

01:49:28.960 --> 01:49:33.200
given that it is public money, it is coming out of the taxpayer's pocket.

01:49:33.200 --> 01:49:36.400
So what is the justification for such a colossal expense,

01:49:37.120 --> 01:49:42.160
given that the vast majority of the population is never going to either attend a concert or

01:49:42.160 --> 01:49:49.600
benefit in any tangible way from that institution? Well, I think it is possible to make some sorts

01:49:49.600 --> 01:49:56.400
of arguments there. But just to compare an even more mainstream example than your Boulez interview

01:49:56.400 --> 01:50:02.240
one, in the 1990s, there was a series here called The House about the Royal Opera House.

01:50:02.240 --> 01:50:07.520
It was a documentary crew who followed them over an extended period. And it's widely credited with

01:50:09.920 --> 01:50:14.880
doing no particular good to the Royal Opera House's reputation, because in this so

01:50:14.880 --> 01:50:20.320
elevated art form, of course, you saw lots of very petty people going about their jobs,

01:50:20.320 --> 01:50:24.640
as you would in any institution of that size. But it sort of rather deflated a lot of its own

01:50:24.640 --> 01:50:36.320
mythology there. But there was one episode which began with the general manager, Jeremy Isaacs,

01:50:37.280 --> 01:50:44.240
traveling to work in a taxi. And I mean, it was clearly a bit set up, but you had the taxi driver

01:50:44.800 --> 01:50:48.800
asking some of the things that taxi drivers in London do. He says, oh, you're Jeremy Isaacs,

01:50:48.800 --> 01:50:53.440
aren't you? He says, yes, I am. Clearly a bit grumpy and not particularly wanted to talk to this

01:50:53.440 --> 01:51:00.080
taxi driver. He said, OK, can you just ask me something? And the taxi driver was framed as

01:51:00.080 --> 01:51:05.520
a quite reasonable way, saying, well, why should all of people like me and other taxpayers who

01:51:05.520 --> 01:51:12.560
never go to the opera, why should our taxes go into this? And he just gave a very grumpy and

01:51:12.560 --> 01:51:15.920
very defensive response. And he says, well, if you're not happy, I suggest you take it up with

01:51:15.920 --> 01:51:22.960
your MP. And he says, we get the lowest subsidy in Europe, which is true. But he wasn't prepared

01:51:22.960 --> 01:51:29.200
to engage the question. And unfortunately, I think that's quite common that people don't want to

01:51:29.200 --> 01:51:36.400
ask this question. Now, you could, I think, articulate an argument in terms of the advancement

01:51:36.400 --> 01:51:43.440
of musical knowledge and musical language, which could be seen as a good in its own right, even

01:51:43.440 --> 01:51:48.720
if only minority actually partake of that. But it could be seen to have other sort of

01:51:49.280 --> 01:51:54.640
side effects and other byproducts. Well, I think if you don't engage the question thoroughly,

01:51:55.520 --> 01:51:58.960
then the danger is that it will simply seem like a form of entitlement.

01:51:59.600 --> 01:52:06.640
Which it is. It is. And do you think the people who are chasing after the commissions on all the

01:52:06.640 --> 01:52:12.560
big festivals in Europe, do you think that many of them have a sense of some sort of wider social

01:52:12.560 --> 01:52:17.040
responsibility? Or do you think they're thinking, what do I have to do to get the most lucrative

01:52:17.040 --> 01:52:22.960
commissions? And many think, well, I am a great composer, or at least I say so. So therefore,

01:52:22.960 --> 01:52:27.840
I should get these commissions. And of course, there's more people wanting them than there are

01:52:27.840 --> 01:52:33.200
commissions to go around. And for one way reason or another, some get the commissions, some don't.

01:52:33.200 --> 01:52:39.040
I'm not saying that's always a fair process. There's lots of factors involved, but then some get very

01:52:39.040 --> 01:52:45.840
embittered because they feel entitled to have these things. But you can sometimes frame their

01:52:45.840 --> 01:52:50.720
entitlement in terms that would make sense to other people in new music, the value of their

01:52:50.720 --> 01:52:55.840
work. But framing them in terms that would make sense to a wider public is quite a bit harder to do.

01:52:57.520 --> 01:53:08.160
And as subsidy is gradually being cut, and as what we might call an avant-garde establishment,

01:53:08.160 --> 01:53:15.200
its position is looking more and more precarious now, including in the light of new diversity

01:53:15.200 --> 01:53:23.200
initiatives, and so on. As that's happening, what you are starting to see is what I think rather

01:53:23.920 --> 01:53:30.160
desperate attempts to sort of suggest some social relevance, which is where you get a lot of music,

01:53:30.160 --> 01:53:40.160
which is distinguish more by which topical issues it fastens itself on to, as if away saying, please

01:53:40.160 --> 01:53:48.000
look, I'm writing a piece about the war in Ukraine, so therefore it's relevant and it's meaningful.

01:53:49.280 --> 01:53:53.360
To which, as I was saying to you before, I would ask, well, why is that a piece of music?

01:53:55.680 --> 01:54:01.760
And if you're writing a sort of, yes, a slow laminato so for string orchestra,

01:54:02.000 --> 01:54:09.920
saying to the dead in Ukraine, I'm sorry, forget it, I've heard 100 pieces of those,

01:54:09.920 --> 01:54:14.640
and you could take them from one traumatic event to another without having to change

01:54:14.640 --> 01:54:22.800
almost anything. I mean, not so many people do that in the new music scene, but they're trying

01:54:22.800 --> 01:54:27.280
to fame discourse around their work in terms of anything other than its musical qualities.

01:54:28.000 --> 01:54:34.640
And musical abstraction and music's lack of an object, music's not being a figurative art

01:54:34.640 --> 01:54:40.240
primarily, of course I recognise as sort of mimetic music and programmatic music and so on,

01:54:40.240 --> 01:54:45.840
but I don't think music is fundamentally a mimetic art and that those things, which I think are

01:54:45.840 --> 01:54:57.920
strengths are seen as weaknesses. And I think this is just emblematic of a new music scene

01:54:57.920 --> 01:55:04.880
that's forced onto the defensive to some extent. The sense of entitlement is not being

01:55:05.440 --> 01:55:13.680
mirrored in wider public discourse, which now lacks prominent and articulate figures such as

01:55:13.680 --> 01:55:19.840
Boulez, such as Stoccas, perhaps such as Carter, but those types of composers, they're all either

01:55:19.840 --> 01:55:25.200
very old or no longer with us now. It was politically expedient in France and Germany and

01:55:25.200 --> 01:55:30.160
other places in the post-war era to support contemporary forms of culture for various reasons.

01:55:31.760 --> 01:55:37.520
It's no longer the case. In fact, it's a liability to the extent that the general

01:55:37.520 --> 01:55:41.840
population even thinks about these things, which I think is highly unlikely, but it's no longer

01:55:42.480 --> 01:55:46.480
it's no longer advantageous to say, well, look what we're doing for the arts, look what we're

01:55:46.480 --> 01:55:52.320
doing for contemporary music. So there's no reason to imagine that it would continue indefinitely.

01:55:52.320 --> 01:56:00.800
And my argument is that this, and to make things clear, I'm not for a minute suggesting that

01:56:00.800 --> 01:56:04.640
everything needs to be left up to market forces. Obviously, there are certain things that cannot

01:56:04.640 --> 01:56:12.720
be left up to the market. And I'm in favor of state support for cultural institutions,

01:56:12.720 --> 01:56:19.120
for museums, for symphony orchestras, for operas, and so on. Where it gets complicated, I think,

01:56:19.120 --> 01:56:24.960
is subsidies to individual artists and how those get decided, how they get distributed.

01:56:26.880 --> 01:56:34.160
That's very tricky. And my sense now is that a better model is some kind of private funding

01:56:34.160 --> 01:56:39.360
or crowdfunding for a lot of projects. And I think that that can actually work quite well.

01:56:39.360 --> 01:56:44.560
And part of the reason for that is there's, in those instances, a direct connection between

01:56:44.560 --> 01:56:49.040
the person commissioning or the group of people commissioning, there's a relationship between

01:56:49.040 --> 01:56:56.720
them and the artist. We open to all sorts of potentials that are corruptibility,

01:56:56.720 --> 01:57:03.840
all sorts of favoritism. It could be some rich people give their private money to other people

01:57:03.840 --> 01:57:08.960
from their own sort of milieu, their own background, and things like that. It could work

01:57:08.960 --> 01:57:13.520
very much against those who are not born to the backgrounds where they're going to have those

01:57:13.520 --> 01:57:24.160
sorts of contacts and things. Moving towards private funding, I wouldn't really see as the way

01:57:24.160 --> 01:57:30.880
forward, to be honest. Crowdfunding as well, that's, I mean, I don't know how sustainable

01:57:30.880 --> 01:57:36.960
that is. I mean, you can do odd projects, but whether someone could sustain enough to sort of

01:57:36.960 --> 01:57:43.840
keep working, I'm less sure. The alternative that's left, then, is making an absolutely

01:57:43.840 --> 01:57:49.680
airtight case for continued public subsidizing of esoteric art forms.

01:57:50.720 --> 01:57:58.480
Yes. And I think that can be done, but maybe the artistic priorities would have to change

01:57:59.200 --> 01:58:08.400
a bit. Maybe a bit more honesty would be needed about the traditions in which these are located.

01:58:08.400 --> 01:58:13.920
I mean, why should we not be equally giving money towards supporting things that are doing

01:58:13.920 --> 01:58:19.280
esoteric things in popular music idioms and traditions? Why would they be any less deserving

01:58:19.840 --> 01:58:24.000
of it? There were quite a lot of extremely violent polemics around that in France,

01:58:24.000 --> 01:58:30.080
actually, or surrounding the Villa Medici, notably. When they decided to open that institution up to

01:58:30.080 --> 01:58:36.320
people working in popular domains, singer-songwriters, for example, and the composers, of course,

01:58:36.320 --> 01:58:42.240
predictably, the older, more established composers were absolutely outraged at the idea that

01:58:42.240 --> 01:58:47.200
you're taking away a spot from us. We need this. We don't have anything else, and you're giving it

01:58:47.200 --> 01:58:51.600
to somebody in the popular field. Unless I know people don't need it. They don't need it.

01:58:52.480 --> 01:58:58.640
If they're doing commercial singer-songwriting, of which there's a long tradition of at least

01:58:58.640 --> 01:59:04.400
some people making a perfectly viable commercial income from that, then I would say they're right

01:59:04.400 --> 01:59:09.360
to say they don't need it. If they were doing something that somehow engages with stylistic

01:59:09.360 --> 01:59:15.280
aspects of it or other aspects of those traditions, but are taking it into some new realms, then that

01:59:15.360 --> 01:59:25.600
might be a different matter. I suppose I do see value in art being able to experiment in art,

01:59:25.600 --> 01:59:32.320
and not just keep doing new experiments from the bottom up, but starting developing new

01:59:32.320 --> 01:59:38.640
idioms and developing them over a period of time. Where's there some continuity across an output?

01:59:38.640 --> 01:59:45.120
I think there is something to be said for supporting that over an extended period.

01:59:45.120 --> 01:59:49.280
And I'll come back to that in terms of what you're saying about premiers in a second.

01:59:52.800 --> 02:00:00.480
Because, well, I would frame it in terms of that I think a society which doesn't

02:00:01.440 --> 02:00:05.600
offer a space for those things to be developed and articulated

02:00:07.520 --> 02:00:12.640
is one that's somewhat impoverished in terms of knowledge, in terms of the forms of experience,

02:00:12.640 --> 02:00:21.200
the forms of thought that are made possible, even if they are for a minority. But most people,

02:00:21.200 --> 02:00:25.520
I believe, have some sort of minority interest. They're just not all the same, or they wouldn't

02:00:25.600 --> 02:00:37.920
be a minority. I've used this sort of analogy with television. Supposing you have

02:00:40.560 --> 02:00:48.160
100 people and 101 television channels, and suppose each of those channels

02:00:49.520 --> 02:00:55.200
is only watched by one of those people, except for the 101st, which everyone watches.

02:00:55.760 --> 02:01:03.120
As well. Do you think any of those people would be happy if you got rid of the 100 and you were

02:01:03.120 --> 02:01:10.640
left with only number 101? There is something to be said for supporting minority interests.

02:01:10.640 --> 02:01:15.520
The problem is, new music seems to sport only one type of quite narrow minority interest, and

02:01:16.400 --> 02:01:24.400
probably some different form of subsidy would have to be spread across a wider range of things,

02:01:24.480 --> 02:01:31.520
where you can produce evidence that across the board, there's a range of engagement with all

02:01:31.520 --> 02:01:37.840
sorts of people at different parts of society. We're a long way from that at the moment.

02:01:37.840 --> 02:01:43.680
Some places more than others. The Huddersfield Festival, for example, is quite open to a very

02:01:43.680 --> 02:01:49.120
broad range of styles and practices. A similar thing happened with-

02:01:49.120 --> 02:01:53.680
Yes, but what about the audiences? I know they do have a local audience at Huddersfield,

02:01:53.680 --> 02:01:57.360
and that matters, and that's been a very important factor in sustaining that festival.

02:01:58.160 --> 02:02:03.040
A local audience, which isn't just visionaries, but just from a local community that have taken

02:02:03.040 --> 02:02:09.040
an interest in it. But still, for all the variety of styles and practices that there are on show at

02:02:09.040 --> 02:02:13.920
Huddersfield, what percentage of the British population, or even the population of parts

02:02:13.920 --> 02:02:20.320
of Yorkshire, ever listen to any of them? If they had a range of things, lots of different

02:02:21.120 --> 02:02:26.320
communities within that geographical area listen to it. It might be a bit different.

02:02:28.080 --> 02:02:32.720
If that is the case already, I'd like to see the evidence for it.

02:02:33.440 --> 02:02:35.760
But I just wondered if I could come back to your question about

02:02:36.640 --> 02:02:40.320
premiers, because I think that's very important. I'm often bemoaned.

02:02:40.320 --> 02:02:53.280
The way that the premier culture permeates so many of the institutions and the events,

02:02:53.920 --> 02:03:00.080
and it's almost invariably seen as a better thing to commission new works or play new

02:03:00.080 --> 02:03:05.600
works that are doing the circuit, than it is to go back to some other works, which might have happened.

02:03:05.920 --> 02:03:14.160
Something, I think, very highly of James Dylan's cycle nine rivers. It was all pretty much

02:03:14.160 --> 02:03:20.800
completed, except for a few details by the early noughties. It's had a few performances,

02:03:20.800 --> 02:03:27.360
but not that many. I think that's an amazing cycle and would really reward more sustained

02:03:27.360 --> 02:03:34.000
exposure. But most people would sooner commission a new work from Dylan if they're at a festival.

02:03:34.480 --> 02:03:39.040
And of course, that has to be, if we didn't have the festivals commissioning things,

02:03:39.040 --> 02:03:43.200
then a lot of the new things wouldn't get written and everything was new at some point in time.

02:03:43.840 --> 02:03:50.880
But I think it's too extreme in terms of, yes, a fetishization of brand new. Something that's

02:03:50.880 --> 02:03:56.320
10 years ago can be, certainly as far as the vast majority of any population's concern,

02:03:56.320 --> 02:04:02.960
will be just as much new music as something written now. And maybe if we had fewer premiers,

02:04:02.960 --> 02:04:07.120
which would actually save some money if you didn't have the same amount of commission fees to pay.

02:04:08.400 --> 02:04:13.040
And a bit more revival of things, and a bit more giving things repeated listening,

02:04:13.040 --> 02:04:18.960
which they definitely need. And also developing a performance tradition more for those things as

02:04:18.960 --> 02:04:24.800
well. Since I've been in Britain on this trip, I've had the opportunity to meet with quite a

02:04:24.800 --> 02:04:31.280
few artistic directors of various ensembles and festivals and organizations. And one of the things

02:04:31.280 --> 02:04:34.960
that's emerged out of that is a lot of these people are very conscious of the need for that.

02:04:34.960 --> 02:04:42.400
And in fact, increasingly inclined to, when contemplating a commission project,

02:04:42.960 --> 02:04:46.720
they'll want to set it up in such a manner that the piece can be played four or five or six times,

02:04:46.720 --> 02:04:51.920
or potentially be taken on tour. And they're increasingly moving away from this very, what

02:04:51.920 --> 02:04:58.400
I think is a very old fashioned and ineffective model of doing a premiere and then moving on to

02:04:58.400 --> 02:05:02.320
the next one. I think that's absurd. And I think that there's a lot of people that are recognizing

02:05:02.320 --> 02:05:09.600
that. And for composers, I would say, don't be shy or hesitant about arguing in favor of that

02:05:09.600 --> 02:05:14.480
when you decide what projects you're going to take on. If the group wants to commission a piece from

02:05:14.480 --> 02:05:20.640
you and has no plans to ever do it again beyond the premiere, then perhaps you may wish to hesitate

02:05:21.440 --> 02:05:22.720
before accepting that project.

02:05:23.840 --> 02:05:31.680
Well, two thoughts there. I mean, absolutely. The move towards networks, I mean, where the

02:05:31.680 --> 02:05:40.880
model is, so a new work will get played in arse musical, it'll get played in Veen Moden,

02:05:40.880 --> 02:05:45.040
it'll get played in Huddersfield, it'll get played in Musica Strasburg, and so on. And

02:05:45.040 --> 02:05:52.080
there are many projects to ensure that commissions don't lead to just one performance,

02:05:52.080 --> 02:05:56.560
but a whole range of them. But it's usually a whole range in quite quick succession after

02:05:56.560 --> 02:06:04.240
each other, usually in one season, at least, so no more than a year. I don't know of networks

02:06:04.240 --> 02:06:07.760
that will have things so that they'll be played once and then played five years later and then

02:06:07.760 --> 02:06:13.840
10 years later, and so on. And I know the objections that there are to some of these

02:06:13.840 --> 02:06:19.520
networks, that it turns the festival circuit into more of a monolith and more homogenous in

02:06:19.520 --> 02:06:27.040
its own way. If basically all the big festivals are just doing the big names and the new works of

02:06:27.040 --> 02:06:33.200
those, that becomes less of a place for more distinct festivals as more of their own sort of

02:06:33.200 --> 02:06:39.360
distinctive nature and character. So I suppose that's, I don't know why you couldn't have a

02:06:39.360 --> 02:06:43.040
festival with its own distinctive character, but still isn't just focused on premiers.

02:06:44.400 --> 02:06:51.120
So there's that factor for start, but there's also the question, are people writing music

02:06:51.920 --> 02:06:55.520
that will last? Or are they even wanting it to last?

02:06:58.880 --> 02:07:06.320
Let me think in the realms of, I mean, we're still talking with our point of reference being the

02:07:06.320 --> 02:07:13.360
work. And in something like free improvisation, that really wouldn't be the case in the same

02:07:13.360 --> 02:07:19.200
way. I mean, yes, there are works of free improvisation, and there are some that are

02:07:19.200 --> 02:07:24.480
perhaps not quite so free or so improvised as suggested to be when they're done on repeated

02:07:24.480 --> 02:07:32.000
occasions and there's quite a lot of commonality between them. But the event perhaps counts for more

02:07:32.000 --> 02:07:39.120
than the work and its permanency in that sort of genre.

02:07:40.000 --> 02:07:45.360
Now, to be fair, not all artists are necessarily preoccupied with posterity.

02:07:46.400 --> 02:07:51.760
And it's a completely legitimate standpoint, I think to say. I'm making things for today,

02:07:51.760 --> 02:07:57.360
and if it lasts and if it doesn't, that's fine. But I'm interested in doing what I

02:07:57.360 --> 02:08:02.960
want to do that reflects the current moment and fate will decide. And it's fine.

02:08:02.960 --> 02:08:10.640
Absolutely fair enough. No one, including the cabozas, can know for sure what will and won't

02:08:10.640 --> 02:08:17.280
last. And trying self-consciously to write things for posterity brings his own set of problems.

02:08:18.320 --> 02:08:23.680
You can see that. So I suppose I wasn't so much thinking of cabozas writing saying,

02:08:23.680 --> 02:08:29.760
well, I'll do the best I can and then let history take its course as far as how it's seen. I was

02:08:29.760 --> 02:08:35.600
thinking rather more of people writing more ephemeral and topical and off-the-moment things.

02:08:38.480 --> 02:08:44.080
And this is where, yes, I'm looking at free improvisation. I'm looking at certain sorts

02:08:44.080 --> 02:08:50.800
of community projects involving amateurs, very in vogue at the moment and so on. And lots of things

02:08:50.800 --> 02:08:56.640
that might be more interesting for the participants and for the listeners.

02:08:57.520 --> 02:09:04.560
And I do think that if I'm really honest, particularly with things involving amateurs,

02:09:05.120 --> 02:09:13.200
it's a bit of a taboo, but I've reached taboo a bit. I'm not so convinced about an awful lot

02:09:13.200 --> 02:09:18.080
of work with amateurs. And I don't really like the role that amateurism has in British musical

02:09:18.080 --> 02:09:25.920
culture overall. I don't think anyone would find it so problematic if I suggested that

02:09:25.920 --> 02:09:33.280
amateur dramatics are mostly for friends and family to see maybe a couple of others.

02:09:35.360 --> 02:09:38.640
Maybe amateur music making is the same.

02:09:38.640 --> 02:09:43.760
Yes, it depends on the level of accomplishment of the amateur, of course. Because in Germany,

02:09:43.760 --> 02:09:49.120
there's of course a very strong tradition of, well, in fact, I know many people

02:09:50.320 --> 02:09:53.520
in Strasbourg, for example, who are professionals in other fields. They might be

02:09:54.240 --> 02:09:57.840
they might be diplomats, they might be working for the Council of Europe, they might be

02:09:59.440 --> 02:10:05.200
who have a degree in music, who are passionate about music, but are simply not pursuing it as

02:10:05.200 --> 02:10:10.080
a career, but who are outstanding performers. Absolutely. The New London Chamber Choir here,

02:10:10.080 --> 02:10:13.280
again, not a professional choir, but one of the most outstanding,

02:10:14.000 --> 02:10:18.000
the Disc of Synaxus' Choral Works is one of the greatest synaxus discs I think there's ever been.

02:10:18.880 --> 02:10:25.200
And yes, some of the amateur choirs there are more widely, not specific to new music.

02:10:26.320 --> 02:10:32.720
There is some fair degree of accomplishment there. But, well, in Britain, I think this means

02:10:32.720 --> 02:10:36.400
that people think rare, therefore, we don't really need many professional choirs. And that's the

02:10:36.400 --> 02:10:42.560
problem I have there. But I'm thinking more of these community projects with amateurs.

02:10:43.280 --> 02:10:49.520
They may form some useful community social function, but I'm not sure they necessarily

02:10:49.520 --> 02:10:56.000
produce really remarkable art. I mean, I've seen some exceptions. Some of the work that people

02:10:56.000 --> 02:11:00.480
like Gerhard Stabler and Konzu Shim have done with amateurs or schoolchildren has been absolutely

02:11:00.480 --> 02:11:09.120
remarkable, I think, really gripping stuff. But it's very directed. I mean, both of them know

02:11:09.120 --> 02:11:15.840
exactly what they want from these people and can get it. But I'm not really sure how much input

02:11:15.840 --> 02:11:21.200
beyond sort of doing what they're told the amateurs and others have in that.

02:11:24.160 --> 02:11:28.080
So what I'm saying is if we're looking for something where you'll have more sustained

02:11:28.080 --> 02:11:33.840
traditions and where we will have repeated performances, there needs to be work which

02:11:33.840 --> 02:11:38.480
will stand up to that. That's quite right. That is quite right. Yes. Yes, you would have to be,

02:11:38.480 --> 02:11:42.960
you would have to be aiming to produce work that can withstand that kind of scrutiny,

02:11:42.960 --> 02:11:49.680
that kind of repeated listening. Yeah. Well, we should probably wrap this up. Before we stop,

02:11:49.680 --> 02:11:53.520
though, is there anything you'd like to tell our listeners about what you're working on currently

02:11:53.520 --> 02:12:01.440
and what you're doing at the moment? Well, things have taken a certain new direction in my

02:12:01.440 --> 02:12:06.160
professional life that I've moved from my university, City University of London,

02:12:06.160 --> 02:12:10.880
I've moved from the music department to the sociology department. I'm now professor of music,

02:12:10.880 --> 02:12:16.080
culture and society here. And there are a lot of continuities in terms of the type of teaching

02:12:16.080 --> 02:12:21.840
I do. I mean, I've taught about music and some aspects of wider culture in social context

02:12:21.840 --> 02:12:27.360
for a long time. And if anything, I probably find there's a more hospitable culture in the

02:12:27.360 --> 02:12:33.120
new department I'm in towards what I'll say is a dialectical view of the relationship between

02:12:33.760 --> 02:12:38.480
what I call culture with a medium-sized C, which means not just high culture,

02:12:38.480 --> 02:12:43.120
can be popular culture as well, but it means things specifically designated as culture.

02:12:43.120 --> 02:12:48.160
It doesn't just mean the whole realm of human activity, which is the more anthropological

02:12:48.160 --> 02:12:53.200
definition. But when I say dialectical model, I mean, between that type of culture and the

02:12:53.200 --> 02:13:00.160
rest of society, there are all sorts of interplays, interactions, but it's not a simple deterministic

02:13:00.160 --> 02:13:04.480
relationship. You can't say because of society's particular way, it'll therefore automatically

02:13:04.480 --> 02:13:10.320
produce this type of culture. The culture isn't just a bright part of society. The culture is

02:13:10.320 --> 02:13:16.320
equally part of society and can exist in a critical relationship with the rest of society.

02:13:16.320 --> 02:13:21.040
Now, that's widely accepted amongst a lot of cultural sociologists, perhaps not so much

02:13:21.040 --> 02:13:26.400
amongst some music sociologists and music anthropologists and so on. So it's actually

02:13:26.480 --> 02:13:34.640
refreshing to find a much more open intellectual culture with respect to that and lots of other

02:13:34.640 --> 02:13:39.680
things in here. So I teach more widely about culture, not just about music, and I teach

02:13:39.680 --> 02:13:45.040
about classical social theory, but I will be teaching more about music as a social phenomenon

02:13:45.760 --> 02:13:52.320
as well. Beyond that, I'm still playing. I've been playing perhaps more traditional repertoire

02:13:52.320 --> 02:14:00.480
in the last few years. In 2022, I did this big cycle of all nine of Liszt's versions of

02:14:00.480 --> 02:14:04.560
Beethoven's symphony, and I followed it up with doing this version of the Symphony Fantastique

02:14:04.560 --> 02:14:10.880
last year of Berlioz as well. And, you know, I'm looking for new and interesting ways of

02:14:10.880 --> 02:14:15.120
combining the old and the new, which is something I've done for a long time, but

02:14:15.920 --> 02:14:21.600
it's more fundamental to me now. So I'm doing that. I'm doing lots of writing. I'm writing a new

02:14:21.680 --> 02:14:27.120
biography of Stockhausen for reaction books. I'm working on other books on musical modernism

02:14:27.120 --> 02:14:32.880
in Germany after 45 and on the history of specialist music schools in Britain

02:14:34.640 --> 02:14:42.320
and a whole range of articles. And I've been writing more for non-academic outlets. I've done

02:14:43.280 --> 02:14:50.160
oh, since, since 2022, I've published only 11 articles in the Times Higher Education

02:14:51.360 --> 02:14:57.200
Journal on lots of things to do with education, including to do with music, but not just that.

02:14:58.240 --> 02:15:04.080
I've written more stuff for the London Review books for the critic, and you're trying to,

02:15:05.120 --> 02:15:10.160
again, not always on music, but very much on cultural issues and cultural and political

02:15:10.160 --> 02:15:15.920
issues. And those things are very important to me. And the opportunity to engage with wider

02:15:15.920 --> 02:15:21.680
audiences, also at public events where I've given talks and things is really important. And

02:15:22.960 --> 02:15:34.160
it's made me realise the value of that for, for academics. I think there is certainly value

02:15:34.160 --> 02:15:38.560
in academics working on something without necessarily knowing where it's going to lead,

02:15:38.560 --> 02:15:43.760
just like we're talking about with musicians. And much knowledge has been generated without

02:15:43.760 --> 02:15:48.160
necessarily clear endpoints at the beginning. And that's a whole nature of research. You don't

02:15:48.160 --> 02:15:54.080
necessarily know what your research will tell you in the end. But that has to come to some point at

02:15:54.080 --> 02:16:04.160
which there is a culture of thought of intellectual activity that if they must, if, if they've never

02:16:04.160 --> 02:16:12.480
had any discernible, even indirect impact outside of small circles, then their, their value, surely

02:16:13.120 --> 02:16:20.080
it's fair to question that. And I've, I've thought about this in the context of academic

02:16:20.080 --> 02:16:25.040
writing on culture, including the realms of cultural studies and so on, which I think is

02:16:25.040 --> 02:16:34.880
distinct from cultural sociology. You can produce any number of journal articles which will get

02:16:34.880 --> 02:16:44.720
hardly read, which have very, very jargon ridden particular takes on cultural phenomena as on.

02:16:45.840 --> 02:16:50.240
Now, I don't expect journal, academic journal articles to be read by a wide readership. They're

02:16:50.240 --> 02:16:54.800
not done for their purpose. But I might expect that some of their core arguments might be distilled

02:16:55.120 --> 02:17:01.760
and find their way into writings for, for a wider audience. And that's to something that what I'm

02:17:01.760 --> 02:17:07.360
trying to do is from my wider writing and things. And that there are academics who are very hostile

02:17:07.360 --> 02:17:14.560
to that. They, they don't ever want to sort of be asked any questions about what the wider impact or

02:17:15.600 --> 02:17:22.160
relevance of their work is. And I think that's unsustainable in the long run. And, you know,

02:17:22.160 --> 02:17:27.680
just like we're talking about possible crises and lack of faith in the realm of new music,

02:17:29.040 --> 02:17:36.400
the same sort of things are happening in universities and certainly in Britain and

02:17:37.760 --> 02:17:41.360
in some other countries, but I think particularly in Britain, now that we have about half the

02:17:42.000 --> 02:17:49.120
population graduating from high school going into university, it's forced questions about

02:17:49.120 --> 02:17:53.920
what university is for. And you can't just answer them in the same way as you did when

02:17:53.920 --> 02:17:58.960
only 20% of the population. It was like, it was something like that or not much more when I was

02:17:58.960 --> 02:18:05.600
a student. And you, the whole model of the relationship between research and teaching

02:18:05.600 --> 02:18:10.720
has to be looked at again, and the whole model of what, which disciplines matter

02:18:10.720 --> 02:18:17.200
inevitably does. And this has been happening, but it's made life difficult for those working in

02:18:17.760 --> 02:18:22.960
what seem like very esoteric disciplines when they're no longer succeeding and generating

02:18:22.960 --> 02:18:31.360
the same interest from young people are studying those things. And you do ultimately need students

02:18:31.360 --> 02:18:35.680
for universities. They're not, they may be primarily research things, but they can't be only

02:18:35.680 --> 02:18:42.560
research things on at least a whole sector can't be sustained that way. And how we can maintain

02:18:43.360 --> 02:18:52.320
aspects of real sort of critical knowledge generation whilst also teaching things that

02:18:52.960 --> 02:18:58.800
young people will find engaging and important. And we can somehow demonstrate to the wider society,

02:18:58.800 --> 02:19:05.120
which we expect to fund our activities, how, how what we do has some other meaning. I think

02:19:05.120 --> 02:19:11.600
those things can't be ignored and need to be ends as difficult times coming ahead. The British

02:19:11.600 --> 02:19:19.680
university sector has been had a situation where fees were frozen in 2017 at 9,250 per year for,

02:19:20.400 --> 02:19:26.880
for home undergraduate students. So in real terms, this means that the amount of money that each

02:19:26.880 --> 02:19:32.800
institution has coming in is going down every year whilst whilst it's frozen that they can't

02:19:32.800 --> 02:19:38.480
go up with inflation. At the same time, Brexit spent a real reduction of EU students,

02:19:38.480 --> 02:19:46.160
new visa laws are making it harder for other foreign students to come. And certain subjects,

02:19:46.880 --> 02:19:53.760
including music, are finding cuts in secondary provision here. So there isn't the same demand

02:19:53.760 --> 02:19:58.960
generated amongst potential students. So we've just recently seen that the music department

02:19:58.960 --> 02:20:04.480
in Oxford Brooks was scheduled to be closed down together with some other departments,

02:20:04.560 --> 02:20:09.440
like including the Department of Mass there. And there were going to be cuts in other

02:20:09.440 --> 02:20:15.280
developed particularly arts and humanities. Unfortunately, I foresee in the next five or

02:20:15.280 --> 02:20:19.360
10 years, because other factors are going to make the financial provision even more precarious in

02:20:19.360 --> 02:20:27.120
universities, we may see other cuts and we need to be adaptable and flexible and be prepared to

02:20:27.120 --> 02:20:31.920
sort of countenance new ideas of what the university is for whilst holding on to what's best here. And

02:20:32.880 --> 02:20:36.560
that's very much what I'm engaged with in what I'm writing about those subjects,

02:20:36.560 --> 02:20:40.560
just like with music. Ian Pace, thank you very much. Always a pleasure to talk with you.

02:20:40.560 --> 02:20:41.920
Likewise, thank you.

